# **************************************************************************
# Device SV5Objects
#

@NODE SVOBJECT_Printer "Printer.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Printer.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It supports printing from any Screen (upto 256 Colors)
  or graphics buffer (upto 256 Colors or 24 Bit).

  The standard printer.device of AmigaOS does not support printing of
  24 Bit graphics (rastports) upto version 3.0. There are three ways
  to pass this by:

    - either dithering to 256 colors before printing
      the 24 Bit graphics (still looks ugly with standard printer drivers)

    - OR installing TurboPrint V3 through V7 by IrseeSoft, which replaces
      printer.device greatly and besides improved 256 color printing
      also offers 24 Bit support

    - OR installing the Studio Printer Software (Studio Professional II or
      any other Studio version like e.g. CanonStudio) by Wolf Faust,
      which consists of an external server program. Printer.sv5object will
      write the graphics as either IFF-ILBM (upto 8 Bit) or PNG (24 Bit),
      and the Studio Server then will read the file, open its GUI and
      allow you to print it, while also being able to do some settings.

    - OR upgrading to OS 3.5+ which supports 24 bit printing

  There are explicit DISABLE_ controlpads for TurboPrint, Studio and
  the OS 3.5 24 bit printing option - otherwise your configuration
  is automatically detected in the following order:

      TurboPrint -> Studio -> OS 3.5 24 Bit -> default

   Printing without installed TurboPrint/Studio (prior OS 3.5)
   -----------------------------------------------------------
   In this case, all 24 Bit images will be dithered to 256 colors
   before printing (using the "Dither24Bit" operator).

   Usually you get best results, when first applying "AnyTo24Bit"
   to a 256 color graphics and then call Printer.sv5object
   from your application's DEVICE SV5Object list.

   Printing with TurboPrint/Studio being installed
   -----------------------------------------------
   When printing 24 Bit graphics, TurboPrint/Studio will automatically
   be used when available. You can do all the necessary settings fromout
   their GUIs.

   Printing under OS 3.5 and beyond
   ---------------------------------
   When printing 24 Bit graphics, and TurboPrint/Studio is not available,
   24 bit printing will be utilized under OS 3.5+ anyway.

  Credits
  ~~~~~~~
  o TurboPrint V7 does support most of the available printers
    and makes these useable with the Amiga. It improves AmigaOS'
    native printer drivers as well as adding 24 Bit capability to
    its printer.device.

    In Germany, TurboPrint can be obtained directly from IrseeSoft,
    but they'll as well be able to tell you a distributor near you:

       ZEDOnet GmbH
       Meinrad-Spieß-Platz 2
       D-87660 Irsee            Voice: +49-(0)8341-908 3 905
       Germany                  Fax:   +49-(0)8341-908 3 906

       ZEDOnet WWW page: http://www.zedonet.de
       ZEDOnet: mail@zedonet.de

    Thanks to Florian Zeiler for providing TurboPrint.

  o Studio Professional II does support many printers, too.

    As of late 2008 it seems to be available only via some dealers,
    e.g. Vesalia in Germany (3,90 EUR plus shipping - www.vesalia.de)

    Thanks to Wolf Faust for providing Studio and CanonStudio.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Printer.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - DENSITY=<density value for printing quality>
                          ; Amiga's printer device does allow seven
                          ; modes of printing density (1-7)
                          ; (not with TurboPrint)
                          ; default is: 3
                        - DISABLE_TURBOPRINT
                          ; If set, TurboPrint support is disabled.
                          ; default is: <not set>
                        - DISABLE_STUDIO
                          ; If set, Studio support is disabled.
                          ; default is: <not set>
                        - DISABLE_OS35_24BIT
                          ; If set, OS 3.5+ 24 Bit support is disabled.
                          ; default is: <not set>
@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_Scanner "Scanner.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Scanner.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It supports scanning images by using Andreas Günther's scanner.device,
  as supplied with the ScanQuix software package.

  Currently, all scanned images are imported as 24 Bit.

  Credits
  ~~~~~~~
  ScanQuix currently supports more than 20 different scanner models:

   Vendor   Model                         Connection
   ---------------------------------------------------------------
   Epson    GT-4000, GT-5000, GT-6000,    SCSI, serial or parallel
            GT-6500, GT-8000, GT-8500,
            GT-9000

   HP       ScanJet 2c, 2cx, 3c, 4c,      SCSI
            4p, 5p

   Mustek   Paragon 600, 600 SP,          SCSI
            600 II SP, 800 SP,
            800 II SP, 1200, 1200 SP

   Artec    ViewStation A6000C,           SCSI
            A6000C Plus, AT-3, AT-6


  It is available from:

  RBM Computertechnik
  Bernd Rudolf            http://www.rbm.de/ScanQuix/
  Kleinenberger Weg 2a    info@rbm.de
  D-33100 Paderborn       Phone: +49-5251-16191-9
  Germany                 Fax:   +49-5251-640655

  As of December 1997, ScanQuix 4 was publicly offered for 179 DM.
  For more information, please contact this company. For a special
  "Artec&ScanQuix3" package you may contact AB Union under:
  http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/AB_Union/


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Scanner.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - PUBSCREEN_NAME=<PubScreenName>
                          ; where the scanner drivers should open
                          ; their windows (if not set or not available,
                          ; the default Public Screen will be used).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_Camedia "Camedia.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Camedia.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It can be used to utilize Andreas Patrick Fleuti's "Camedia" tool
  to import JPEG pictures from a connected Olympus digital camera
  into your Amiga.

  This SV5Object still is in some kind of beta status and hasn't been
  extensively tested, though - as the Camedia tool itself.

  Import of images from C-900 Zoom, 400Z or C400L should work.


  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:comm/misc/Camedia.lha


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Camedia.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling Camedia,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 32768
                        - CAMEDIA_PATH=<camedia command path plus name>
                          ; how camedia is to be called
                          ; e.g. CAMEDIA_PATH=Work:Camedia/Camedia
                          ; default is: camedia
                        - PICNUMBER=<number of picture>
                          ; which picture (identified by number)
                          ; should be imported from the camera ?
                          ; default is: 1
                        - DEVICE=<Name of serial device>
                          ; UNIT and SPEED *must* be specified, too
                        - UNIT=<unit of serial device>
                          ; DEVICE and SPEED *must* be specified, too
                        - SPEED=<9600..115200>
                          ; DEVICE and UNIT *must* be specified, too

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_DCRAW "DCRAW.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  DCRAW.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It can be used to utilize Dave Coffin's "dcraw" tool to import digital camera
  raw images into SView5-Library, including a number of import options..

  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:comm/misc/#?dcraw#?.lha


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/DCRAW.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling dcraw,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 524280
                        - DCRAW_PATH=<dcraw command path plus name>
                          ; how dcraw is to be called
                          ; e.g. DCRAW_PATH=Work:DCRAW/dcraw
                          ; default is: dcraw
                        - PICNUMBER=<0..99>
                          ; which picture (identified by number)
                          ; should be imported from the raw file?
                          ; default is: 0
                      : - EXTRACTMODE=<IMAGE|PREVIEW>
                          ; Determines, whether the preview image or
                          ; the full size image part should be extracted
                          ; default is: IMAGE
                      : - FORMAT=<8BIT|16BIT>
                          ; Determines, whether 8 bit (24 bit) or 16 bit (48 bit)
                          ; image raw data should be extracted
                          ; default is: 8BIT
                      : - METAFORMAT=<PPM|TIFF>
                          ; Determines, whether to use PPM or TIFF as vehicle
                          ; for importing the raw image data; TIFF may allow for
                          ; meta data import in the future as well (depends on dcraw)
                          ; default is: PPM
                      : - COLORSPACE=<RAW|SRGB|ADOB|WIDE|PRO|XYZ>
                          ; Determines, which color space to use when importing raw
                          ; data - note, that this option only makes sense with
                          ; METAFORMAT=TIFF and not all options may be fully supported.
                          ; It is recommended to use RAW or SRGB.
                          ; default is: RAW

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_ExifTool "ExifTool.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ExifTool.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It supports importing meta data, by means of directly extracing it
  from the graphics file it belongs to - in detail the following
  meta data is supported:

   - XMP (as XMP1)

  Import is carried out by the powerful "ExifTool" Perl script from
  Phil Harvey plus a working Perl installation. Both must be installed
  and configured accordingly.

  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:comm/misc/#?exiftool#?.lha

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/ExifTool.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling exiftool,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 65536
                        - PERL_PATH=<perl command path plus name>
                          ; how perl is to be called
                          ; e.g. PERL_PATH=ADE:bin/perl
                          ; default is: ADE:bin/perl
                        - EXIFTOOL_PATH=<exiftool script path plus name>
                          ; how ExifTool is to be called
                          ; e.g. EXIFTOOL_PATH=Work:ExifTool/exiftool
                          ; default is: exiftool
                        - LOADNAME=<filename>
                          ; File to load (suppress file requester)
                          ; use this if you write an ARexx script

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_FxPaintStargate "FxPaintStargate.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  FxPaintStargate.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It can be used to quickly export images from SView to FxPAINT by
  Felix Schwarz.

  Every graphics will be converted to 24 Bit RGB data before it is
  exported, and then via a "hotlink" kind of connection directly
  will be moved over to FxPAINT - which has to be running at the
  same time, of course.


  Credits
  ~~~~~~~
  Thanks to Felix Schwarz for providing me with a copy of FxPAINT
  to allow for implementation of such a module.

  Ask your local dealer for information on how to obtain FxPAINT.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_NETPBM "NetPBM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  NetPBM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It can be used to utilize the NetPBM package's external tools to
  images into SView5-Library.

  Any kind of format supported by NetPBM first will be converted to
  PNM (PBM, PGM or PPM) using these tools, and then imported directly
  into SView5-Library.

  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:comm/misc/#?NetPBM#?.lha


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/NETPBM.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling dcraw,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 65536
                        - NETPBM_PATH=<netpbm command path>
                          ; folder from where NetPBM is to be called
                          ; e.g. NETPBM_PATH=Work:NetPBM/
                          ; default is: c:
                        - REQUEST_LOADER
                          ; if this option is set, the user is always
                          ; asked which NetPBM tool is to be used,
                          ; e.g. giftopnm
                        - NETPBM_LOADER=<netpbm command name>
                          ; NetPBM tool to be called
                          ; default is: giftopnm
                        - NETPBM_LOADER_OPTIONS=<netpbm command options>
                          ; options for NetPBM tool to be called
                          ; default is: <none>
                        - LOADNAME=<filename>
                          ; File to load (suppress file requester)
                          ; use this if you write an ARexx script

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_RAWImport "RAW-IMPORT.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  RAW-IMPORT.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It supports importing RAW graphics files (pattern <filename>.raw)
  of the following formats:

   -  LUT8    ( 8 bit chunky/planar, with colormap in <filename>.cm) (**)
   -  GRAY8   ( 8 bit gray)
   -  RGB15   (15 bit  RGB + 0 bit A - 0:5:5:5)
   -  RGB16   (16 bit  RGB           -   5:6:5)
   - ARGB16   (15 bit ARGB + 1 bit A - 1:5:5:5)
   -  RGB24   (24 bit  RGB)
   - RGBA32   (32 bit RGBA)
   - ARGB32   (32 bit ARGB)
   - RGB+A32  (24 bit  RGB + 8 bit A) (*)
   -  RGB48   (48 bit  RGB)
   -  RGBA64  (64 bit RGBA)
   - ARGB64   (64 bit ARGB)
   -  RGB+A64 (48 bit  RGB + 16 bit A) (*)
   - BAYER8   ( 8 bit Bayer Matrix) (*)

  (*)  as written by @{"RAW.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_RAW }
  (**) ...in combination with @{"RAW-CM.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_RAW-CM }

  Usage
  ~~~~~
  - first you define the endianess, format, width and height of the file
    by controlpad settings
  - then you ask to load a file from the "device", which in turn just
    opens a file requester with "#?.raw" filter, where you may select
    a suitable file for import (see also the notes below)

  Note
  ~~~~
  - supports endian conversion for 15/16, 24 and 48 bit RGB variants,
    i.e. BGR->RGB (24) and RGB->RGB (48); for 24 bit this means
    that the BGR order is swapped to RGB, for 48 bit this means
    that the byte order within the 16 bit R,G,B values is swapped,
    for 15/16 bit this means swapping of the bytes within the 16 bit word
  - that conversion is only done for ENDIAN=LITTLE
  - if the filesize does not match the given controlpad
    "specifications" file import will fail with an error:

      - for general .raw file rules see @{"RAW.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_RAW }
      - for general .cm file rules see @{"RAW-CM.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_RAW-CM }
      - for LUT8 planar files, it must be a multiple of a single
        ILBM-style uncompressed bitplane


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/RAW-IMPORT.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - ENDIAN=<BIG|LITTLE>
                          ; Endianess of 24/48 bit RGB data
                          ; (24: BGR->RGB, 48: RGB->RGB)
                          ; default: BIG
                        - FORMAT=<LUT8|GRAY8|RGB24|RGBA32|ARGB32|
                                  RGB+A32|RGB48|RGBA64|ARGB64|
                                  RGB+A64|BAYER8>
                          ; Kind of RAW format to be imported
                          ; default: GRAY8
                        - LUT8_FORMAT=<CHUNKY|PLANAR>
                          ; Kind of LUT8 flavour to be imported
                          ; default: CHUNKY
                        - WIDTH=<value>
                          ; Pixel width of RAW data to be imported
                          ; default is: 1
                        - HEIGHT=<value>
                          ; Pixel height of RAW data to be imported
                          ; default is: 1
                        - LOADNAME=<filename>
                          ; File to load (suppress file requester)
                          ; use this if you write an ARexx script
                        - LOAD_CM=<ON|OFF>
                          ; GRAY8/LUT8: check for .cm file and load it?
@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_RAWMetaImport "RAW-META-IMPORT.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  RAW-META-IMPORT.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It supports importing RAW meta data files (usually belonging to graphics
  files of some kind) - in detail these are:

   - EXIF
   - IPTC
   - XMP0
   - XMP1
   - IFF-style meta chunks plaintext (AUTH, ANNO, COPY, NAME)

  (*)  as written by @{"RAW-META.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_RAW-META }

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/RAW-META-IMPORT.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling dcraw,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 65536
                        - FORMAT=<EXIF|IPTC|XMP0|XMP1|AUTH|ANNO|COPY|NAME>
                          ; Kind of RAW format to be imported
                          ; default: EXIF
                        - WIDTH=<value>
                          ; width of dummy graphics to be created for import
                          ; default: 1
                        - HEIGHT=<value>
                          ; height of dummy graphics to be created for import
                          ; default: 1
                        - DEPTH=<8|24|48>
                          ; width of dummy graphics to be created for import
                          ; default: 8
                        - LOADNAME=<filename>
                          ; File to load (suppress file requester)
                          ; use this if you write an ARexx script

@ENDNODE

# **************************************************************************
# SV5Objects
#

@NODE SVOBJECT_AmiFIG "AmiFIG.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  AmiFIG.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support, a working
  GhostScript.sv5object and an installed fig2dev executeable.

  It supports importing AmiFIG/Xfig vector drawings as bitmapped graphics.
  This is done by using fig2dev for conversion to Postscript (TM) files,
  which then will be parsed using a working Ghostscript installation
  with @{"GhostScript.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_GhostScript }.
  Alternatively, you now can redirect FIG handling to @{"MetaView.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_MetaView }.

  AmiFIG.sv5object will create a temporary file, which then will be
  parsed through sview5.library again.

  Reading:

   (Any FIG drawings as long as the resulting Postscript (TM) commands
    are readable for Ghostscript).


  Configuration
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  This FIG support module has been tested with:
   - the AmiFIG 1.1 port from Aminet: AmiFIG is (C) 1996 Andreas Schmidt
  AND NOT YET, because of missing fig2dev:
   - the Xfig 1.9d amiga port from AmiNet, which has been done
     by Terje Pedersen (terjepe@login.eunet.no)

  At first, you have to correctly install and configure Ghostscript
  and @{"GhostScript.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_GhostScript }.

  After that you have to install AmiFIG/Xfig and either supply an AmigaDOS
  search path to a directory, where the executable "fig2dev" is stored
  (default), or explicitely specify path plus name of the program by
  the controlpad entry AMIFIG_PATH (see below).


  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:gfx/edit/Amifig#?.lha  (#?=version and CPU)


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/AmiFIG.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling fig2dev,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 32768
                        - AMIFIG_PATH=<fig2dev command path plus name>
                          ; how fig2dev is to be called
                          ; e.g. AMIFIG_PATH=Work:AmiFIG/fig2dev
                          ; default is: fig2dev
                        - STATUS=<ENABLED|DISABLED>
                          ; allows to disable this module - for example
                          ; to be able to use an other, program-specific
                          ; import-module for the same file format

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_DDS "DDS.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  DDS.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,

  It supports reading and writing of DDS (MS DX10 and DXT 1/2/3/4/5) texture files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - DDS DX10 12 bit uncompressed (  4:4:4), optionally with 4 bit alpha channel (4:4:4:4)
   - DDS DX10 15 bit uncompressed (  5:5:5), optionally with 1 bit alpha channel (1:5:5:5)
   - DDS DX10 16 bit uncompressed (  5:6:5)
   - DDS DX10 24 bit uncompressed
   - DDS DX10 32 bit uncompressed (0:8:8:8), optionally with alpha channel (8:8:8:8)

   - DDS DXT1 16 bit   compressed (  5:6:5), optionally with 1 bit alpha channel (1:5:6:5)
   - DDS DXT2 16 bit   compressed (  5:6:5), optionally with 2 bit alpha channel (2:5:6:5)
   - DDS DXT3 16 bit   compressed (  5:6:5), optionally with 2 bit alpha channel (2:5:6:5)
   - DDS DXT4 16 bit   compressed (  5:6:5), optionally with 4 bit alpha channel (4:5:6:5)
   - DDS DXT5 16 bit   compressed (  5:6:5), optionally with 4 bit alpha channel (4:5:6:6)

  Writing:

   - DDS DX10 32 bit uncompressed (0:8:8:8), optionally with alpha channel (8:8:8:8)

  Notes for writing tools
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   - DXT1: if you do not need alpha information, strip it prior saving in order to improve
     image quality; it directly relates to each other due to the used compression method
   - DXT5: uses 6/8 alpha interpolation, so that 0/255 always are mapped

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_Degas "Degas.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Degas.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of Atari Degas files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - uncompressed Degas PI1 320x200, 16 colors
   - uncompressed Degas PI2 640x200,  4 colors
   - uncompressed Degas PI3 640x400,  2 colors

   - compressed Degas PC1 320x200, 16 colors
   - compressed Degas PC2 640x200,  4 colors
   - compressed Degas PC3 640x400,  2 colors

  For uncompressed files the file extension does not
  matter, but for compressed files it needs to be .PC1/PC2/PC3

  The filesize of uncompressed files must be exactly 32034 bytes.
  A size of 32066 is also tolerated (even though not standard).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_HDR "HDR.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  HDR.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of HDR Radiance files,
  i.e. "High Dynamic Range" encoded images in the float-
  based format of the "Radiance" toolkit.

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - HDR import to 24 bit TrueColor (binary 8:8:8 RGB)

  Writing:

   - HDR export from 24 bit TrueColor (binary 8:8:8 RGB)

  Notes
  ~~~~~
   - HDR files are very different from normal raster graphics
   - therefore, the only reason to use the HDR format in
     a regular application is to interchange data with
     HDR-aware applications and/or to make the migration
     between pre- and post-processing of raw image data
   - in this context pre-processing means image capturing
     and mastering and post-processing means image display
     and rendering
   - in case a HDR file is not recognized, please make sure
     that the first characters in the file are "#?RADIANCE"
     ("#?RGBE" is also accepted, although broken) - if this
     is not the case, you may try to edit a copy of the
     file using a binary-aware text editor or a hex editor
     and try it again

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_IFF-ILBM "ILBM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ILBM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bitplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of IFF-ILBM files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - IFF-ILBM uncompressed            1..8/24/48 bit (optionally alpha)
   - IFF-ILBM CmpByteRun1 compressed  1..8/24/48 bit (optionally alpha)

  Writing:

   - IFF-ILBM uncompressed            1..8/24/48 bit (optionally alpha)
   - IFF-ILBM CmpByteRun1 compressed  1..8/24/48 bit (optionally alpha)

  Notes
  ~~~~~
  Reading/writing from/to ClipBoard is supported.

  Reading/writing an alpha channel is supported for 24 bit files,
  resulting in 32 bit RGBA files (32 planes) compliant to the
  IFF-ILBM extension by NewTek,
  and for 48 bit files,  resulting in 64 bit RGBA files (64 planes)
  as an own (logical) extension introduced by SView5-Library in
  analogy to the PNG file format.

  Sets mskHasAlpha, but with transparent(Color) := 0.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/ILBM.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - ANIM_BODIES
                          ; if set, ANIM files' ILBM-BODY chunk
                          ; (first frame) will be extracted when
                          ; such a file is encountered. Otherwise
                          ; anim.datatype may do that task later.
                          ; (not actually IFF-ILBM support: it's
                          ;  IFF-ANIM support)
                        - IGNORE_CAMG
                          ; tries to avoid possible problems on
                          ; the Draco/Pegasos computer (modeid generation)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_IFF-META "METADATA.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  METADATA.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which extracts only the metadata from graphics files.

  It supports writing and writing of IFF-META files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   Creates empty image with metadata of size [bmhd]
   and empty alpha channel if indicated in [bmhd].
   If [bmhd] is not present, size is 320x240x8.

  Writing (chunks):

   - IFF-BMHD   ; size and dimensions of original graphics, like in ILBM

   - IFF-AUTH   ; see IFF spec
   - IFF-ANNO   ; see IFF spec
   - IFF-Copy   ; see IFF spec
   - IFF-NAME   ; see IFF spec
   - IFF-EXIF   ; see IFF-metadata spec
   - IFF-IPTC   ; see IFF-metadata spec
   - IFF-XMP0   ; see IFF-metadata spec
   - IFF-XMP1   ; see IFF-metadata spec

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_RAW-ALPHA "RAW-ALPHA.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  RAW-ALPHA.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which extracts only the alpha channel from graphics files.

  It supports writing of raw alpha data files.
  In detail these are:

  Writing (chunks):

   - 8 bit alpha for 24 bit images (fully opaque in none present)
   - 8 bit alpha for 48 bit images (fully opaque in none present)

  The file comment includes the type of data.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_RAW-META "RAW-META.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  RAW-META.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which extracts only the metadata from graphics files.

  It supports writing of raw metadata files.
  In detail these are:

  Writing (chunks):

   - EXIF       ; like in IFF-metadata spec, but raw chunk data (payload)
   - IPTC       ; like in IFF-metadata spec, but raw chunk data (payload)
   - XMP0       ; like in IFF-metadata spec, but raw chunk data (payload)
   - XMP1       ; like in IFF-metadata spec, but raw chunk data (payload)

  The file comment includes the type of data and its length.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/RAW-META.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - TEXT_FIELD=<Auth|Anno|Copy|Name|More1|More2|More3|More4>
                          ; Metadata text to extract (for "RAW-META (Text)")
                          ; default: Copy
                        - IPTC_TYPE=<RAW|APP13>
                          ; Include APP13 PS3 8BIM Header?
                          ; default: RAW
                        - EXIF_TYPE=<RAW|APP1>
                          ; Include APP1 EXIF Header?
                          ; default: APP1

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_IFF-PBM "PBM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PBM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of IFF-PBM files, which originally
  only were written by Deluxe Paint II for the PC, when saving
  chunky 256 Color graphics.

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - IFF-PBM uncompressed            8 Bit
   - IFF-PBM CmpByteRun1 compressed  8 Bit

  Writing:

   - IFF-PBM uncompressed            8 Bit  (less than 256 colors will be
   - IFF-PBM CmpByteRun1 compressed  8 Bit   increased to 256 colors)

  Reading/writing from/to ClipBoard is supported.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_IFF-ACBM "ACBM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ACBM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bitplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of IFF-ACBM files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - IFF-ACBM uncompressed 1..8 Bit

  Writing:

   - IFF-ACBM uncompressed 1..8 Bit

  Reading/writing from/to ClipBoard is supported.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_DATATYPES "Datatypes support"

Loading Graphics via DataTypes under OS3
========================================

In General
----------
The library generally also accesses OS3-Datatypes, if none of the
installed SV5Objects was able to identify a specific graphics file format.

Only Datatypes of class "picture" will be accepted.

Specific Problems
-----------------
As you may have expected, it is as well possible to replace single
SV5Objects by the corresponding Datatypes in case you think that
the Datatype does work better or more reliable.

For temporarily enabling this, you would just have to "Remove" the
SV5Object and load the Datatype.
For permanently enabling this, you would have to delete the SV5Object
from "LIBS:sv5objects".

But remember, that DTs in general cannot export 24 bit Data and
are not able to save any graphics (other than as IFF-ILBM).

Ralph Schmidt's picture.datatype V43 does allow loading of 24 bit
pictures by enhancing the datatype system with additional functionality.
To be able using these features with SView5, you need a working
installation of picture.datatype V43 (with ECS/AGA you'll also need a
version of cyberncg.library, which had been removed from newer pic-dt 43
distributions).

The picture.datatype V43 which is coming with the Picasso96 Workbench
Emulation RTG Software should work as well - any problems with this
one should be reported to its author in the first place, though.

This also applies to any other, future picture.datatype V43 clones.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PCX "PCX.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PCX.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of PCX files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

     2-256 Colors, 24 bit. In detail:

      - PCX V2.5  upto 16 Colors (supports 4/8 color EGA/VGA palette)
      - PCX V2.8a upto 16 Colors (supports 4/8 color EGA/VGA palette)
      - PCX V2.8b upto 16 GrayScales
      - PCX V3.00 upto 256 Colors
      - PCX V2.5 - V3.00 with 24 bit Data (see Remarks !)

  Writing:

   Depending on the Colordepth of the source the following is written :

   Source Colors    Version      Type              Destination Colors

    2 ..  16        PCX V2.8a    planar bitmap      16
   32 .. 256        PCX V3.00    chunky pixel      256
   (24 bit)         PCX V3.00    RGB planar        (24 bit)

   For 2-256 Colors It is always tried, to write the files RLE-encoded,
   but if encoding is ineffective (output data nearly as large or even
   larger than input data), the files will be written unencoded.
   24 bit files will currently only be written unencoded.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_QL "QL.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  QL.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of Sinclair QL Graphics files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   Format       Dimensions           Colors     Size

   QL4           512x256             4          32768
   QL8           512x256             8          32768

   Additionally the following variants are - experimentally -
   supported if support is enabled (cf. below):

   QL 4:3        512x256 (% 128)                 49152
   EGA           640x350 (% 160)                 56000
   VGA           640x480 (% 160)                 76800
   SVGA          800x600 (% 200)                120000
   Q40          1024x512 (% 256)                131072
   QPC/Aurora   1024x768 (% 256)                196608
   Extended      768x280 (% 192)                 53760
   QPC           768x384 (% 192)                 73728
   Aurora        768x576 (% 192)                110592

   Not all formats may work in every version.

  Note
  ~~~~
  Only files with a length of 32768 bytes plus the filename extension
  ".QL4", ".QL8" or just ".QL" will be recognized.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/QL.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - QL_MODE=<AUTO|QL4|QL8>
                          ; Determine QL mode from file extension
                          ; automatically, or use mode 4/8 explicitely?
                        - EXOTIC_FORMATS
                          ; Setting this keyword will enable exotic
                          ; formats support as described above;
                          ; not all formats may work in every version

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_Spectrum "Spectrum.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Spectrum.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of ZX Spectrum Graphics files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   Format    Dimensions            Colors

   SCR       256x192               16
   TAP       256x192               16
   ZX        256x192               16
   $C        256x192               16

  Writing:

   Format    Dimensions            Colors

   SCR       256x192               2
   TAP       256x192               2

   If the image has more than 2 colors (should be: black and white)
   it will be dithered down using the Hilbert operator. Also, if
   the size does not match, it will be scaled using the Resize
   operator (note: will fail, if preset scale size does not match).

  Note
  ~~~~
  With ".scr" size 6912 is accepted.
  With ".tap" size 6937 is accepted.
  With ".zx" sizes 6912, 6921 and 6924 are accepted.
  With ".$c" size 6929 is accepted.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_SVG "SVG.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  SVG.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of SGX Graphics files, which is
  SView5-Library's own graphics file format with LZ77/XPK(*) support.

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - SGX  ONEPLANE 8/24 bit
          BITPLANE 1..8 Bit

  Writing:

   - SGX ONEPLANE 8/24 bit
         BITPLANE 1..8 Bit

  Reading/writing an alpha channel is supported for 24 bit files,
  resulting effectively in 32 Bit RGBA files (8:8:8:8) compliant
  to the alpha channel encoding commonly used (e.g. in PNG).

  (*) XPK is deprecated (SVG sub-type); use LZ77 and SGX sub-type

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/SVG.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - PACKMETHOD=<xxxx>
                          ; if this one is specified, it is tried to
                          ; pack the resulting file with the specified
                          ; XPK-Packer. If this fails, the file keeps
                          ; unpacked.
                        - Z_COMPRESSION=<0..9>
                          ; allows changes in compression/speed.
                          ; 0 results in uncompressed data, 9 compresses
                          ; best, but increases decompression time.
                          ; Default: 6

  File Format Information
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  As "Aminet:util/dtype/akSGX-dt.lha" there's a separate package available,
  which consists of a SGX datatype for applications not using
  SView5-Library, the description of the file format and
  a conversion tool for "any-to-SGX" conversion (using Datatypes upto 24 Bit).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_SVGW3C "SVG-W3C.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  SVG-W3C.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of SVG (W3C), which is
  the recommended WWW format for "Scalable Vector Graphics".

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) (as 24/32 bit PNG)

  Writing:

   - SVG (as above, but only Black & White Shapes)

  The import of SVG files is done using an external tool called
  "svg2png" which is available on Aminet (e.g. for MorphOS)
  and converts the input SVG file to PNG. This PNG then is
  loaded by the SV5Object. Alpha channel supported.

  Optionally, for saving (black & white shapes in form of)
  SVG files, the tool "potrace" from Aminet is required.


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/SVG-W3C.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling svg2png
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 32768
                        - SVG2PNG_PATH=<svg2png command path plus name>
                          ; how SVG2PNG is to be called
                          ; e.g. SVG2PNG_PATH=Work:SVGTools/svg2png
                          ; default is: svg2png (FOR LOADING)
                        - POTRACE_PATH=<potrace command path plus name>
                          ; how POTRACE is to be called
                          ; e.g. POTRACE_PATH=Work:potrace-1.7/bin/potrace.elf
                          ; default is: potrace
                        - WIDTH=<value>
                          ; stretch to given width
                          ; default is: - (do not stretch)
                        - HEIGHT=<value>
                          ; stretch to given width
                          ; default is: - (do not stretch)
                        - POTRACE_COLOR=<hex value>
                          ; Line color for potrace (default: black)
                          ; default is: (black)
                        - POTRACE_FILLCOLOR=<hex value>
                          ; Fill color for potrace (default: transparent)
                          ; default is: (transparent)
                        - POTRACE_OPAQUE=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Make white shapes opaque with potrace?
                          ; default is: OFF
                        - POTRACE_INVERT=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Invert Bitmap with potrace?
                          ; default is: OFF
                        - STATUS=<ENABLED|DISABLED>
                          ; allows to disable this module - for example
                          ; to be able to use an other, program-specific
                          ; import-module for the same file format

  Note
  ~~~~
  Files must have the extension .svg in order to be properly
  recognized and loaded.


  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Under "Aminet:gfx/misc" there are "SVGTools" available for MorphOS.
  "svg2png" can be found within this package for example.

  The tool "potrace" is also available there in different flavours,
  for example under "Aminet:gfx/conv".

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_GPlot "GPlot.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  GPlot.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support, a working
  GhostScript.sv5object and an installed GPlot executeable.

  It supports importing CGM metafile vector drawings as bitmapped graphics.
  This is done by using gplot for conversion to Postscript (TM) files,
  which then will be parsed using a working Ghostscript installation
  with @{"GhostScript.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_GhostScript }.
  Alternatively, you now can redirect CGM handling to @{"MetaView.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_MetaView }.

  GPlot.sv5object will create a temporary file, which then will be
  parsed through sview5.library again.

  Reading:

   (Any CGM drawings as long as the resulting Postscript (TM) commands
    are readable for Ghostscript - especially the Times-Roman font has
    to be available for Ghostscript).


  Configuration
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  This CGM/GPlot support module has been tested with the GPlot 4.3b2a1
  port from Aminet:gfx/conv. GPlot is (C) 1987 by the Pittsburgh Su Center,
  the original version had been done by Phil Andres, Amiga port by
  Michael Cheng in 1996.

  At first, you have to correctly install and configure Ghostscript
  and @{"GhostScript.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_GhostScript }.

  After that you have to install GPlot and either supply an AmigaDOS
  search path to a directory, where the executable "GPlot" is stored
  (default), or explicitely specify path plus name of the program by
  the controlpad entry GPLOT_PATH (see below).

  Please note, that the resulting Postscript (TM) files, which then
  will be passed through Ghostscript, definitely do contain a reference
  to the font "Times-Roman" (in Ghostscript's FONTMAP this is redirected
  to the font file ptmr.gsf, which has to be present in the font
  directory(ies) specified in the environment variable GS_LIB).
  With the Ghostscript version I had for testing, the font support
  did not work, due to a bug (or configuration fault ;-) of Ghostscript.

  So, please make sure, that this font is present - otherwise an error
  message like "file not found" may appear.


  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:gfx/conv/gplot.lha


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/GPlot.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling GPlot,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 32768
                        - GPLOT_PATH=<gplot command path plus name>
                          ; how gplot is to be called
                          ; e.g. GPLOT_PATH=Work:GPlot/GPlot
                          ; default is: GPlot
                        - STATUS=<ENABLED|DISABLED>
                          ; allows to disable this module - for example
                          ; to be able to use an other, program-specific
                          ; import-module for the same file format

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_BMP "BMP.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  BMP.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of Windows (TM) and OS/2 (TM)
  BitMap files (BMP). Not all derivates might be supported, though.
  Extraction of Bitmaps from RIFF-BMP files (DIB) also is possible.

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   Windows BMP:  - unencoded        in 1, 4, 8, 16, 24, 32 Bit colordepth
                 - RLE-encoded      in    4, 8             Bit colordepth
                 - bitfield-encoded in              24, 32 Bit colordepth

   OS/2 1.x BMP: - unencoded   in 1, 4, 8, 16, 24, 32 bit colordepth

   Note, that 32 Bit bitfield encoding is 24 Bit + Alpha channel.

  Writing:

   Depending on the Colordepth of the source the following is written :

   Source Depth        Version      Type              Dest Depth

           2           BMP (misc)   packed chk. pix.       1 Bit
    4 ..  16           BMP (misc)   packed chk. pix.       4 Bit
   32 .. 256           BMP (misc)   chunky pixel           8 Bit
      24 Bit           BMP (misc)   RGB pixel             24 Bit
      24 bit + alpha   BMP V4       ARGB bitfield         32 Bit

   The files are written plainly uncompressed (mode 0)
   for 1-24 Bit and using bitfield encoding (mode 3) for 32 Bit.

   Note, that OS/2 might fail to read 32 Bit files, so if you
   plan to use 24 Bit output under OS/2 please ensure that
   the alpha channel has been stripped prior to saving (use
   StripAlpha operator).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_AmiIcon "AmiIcon.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  AmiIcon.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bitplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of Amiga Icon (.info) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - plain 4/8 color icons
   - 16 color icons with MagicWB palette

   When newicon.library is present, it will be used for reading icons
   instead of icon.library. This means, the following types of icons
   are supported, too:

   - NewIcons with a max. size of 93x93 and max. 256 colors

  Writing:

   - plain 4/8 color icons, using BEST PEN color adjustment
   - 16 color icons with MagicWB palette, using BEST PEN color adjustment

   When newicon.library is present, it will be used for writing icons
   instead of icon.library - as long as the icon size is smaller or
   equal than 93x93. With newicon.library 40.1 also a minimum of
   32 colors is required to actually activate the "newicon" mode.
   This means, the following types of icons are written, too:

   - NewIcons with a max. size of 93x93 and 32..256 colors,
     additionally containg the corresponding plain or MagicWB
     icon data

  Note
  ~~~~
  Reading explicitely needs to be enabled
  by a Controlpad setting switch!

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/AmiIcon.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - ICON_DEPTH=<colordepth>
                          ; Depth of icon to be saved.
                          ; Also: WB (depth=2-3, 4-8 colors) or
                          ; MagicWB (depth=4, 16 colors) ?
                          ; default is: 2
                        - ICON_TYPE=<DISK|DRAWER|TOOL|PROJECT|GARBAGE>
                          ; Type of icon to be saved.
                          ; default is: PROJECT
                        - ICON_TOOL=<program name>
                          ; The default tool of the icon to be saved.
                          ; default is: "InsertHere"   ;)
                        - WRITE_NEWICON=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Write NewIcons, when there is newicon.library
                          ; available ?
                          ; Default is: ON
                        - READ_SUPPORT=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Allow reading of icons at all ?
                          ; Default is: OFF
                        - LOAD_WHICH=<OS_31|OS_35>
                          ; Read OS 3.5 or Standard/NewIcon content ?
                          ; (if there's no OS 3.5 content, OS_35 will
                          ;  automatically fall back to Standard/NewIcon
                          ;  content, when available and allowed)
                          ; Default is: OS_35
                        - WHICH_SIDE=<NORMAL|SELECTED>
                          ; Load the normal or selected side of the icon ?
                          ; Default is: NORMAL
                        - SAVE_WHICH=<OS_31|OS_35>
                          ; With WRITE_NEWICON=ON, OS_31 will only write
                          ; the Standard+NewIcon, while OS_35 will rewrite
                          ; the whole icon again as OS 3.5 icon, but
                          ; keeping the NewIcon part (thus writing a
                          ; double-style icon). Filesize will increase.
                          ; Default is: OS_35

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_CT "Scitex.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  CT.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with 24 bit Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of Scitex CT/SCT pre-press/print files.
  In detail these are:

   Colors Depth  Organisation

    ( 8  Bit)    8 bit grayscale CT/SCT
    (32  Bit)    24 bit CT/SCT

  Note, that loading CMYK files is not yet supported to due
  a lack of sample files (and since those may be pretty
  hardware-dependent).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_CUT "CUT.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  CUT.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of Dr. Halo (CUT/PAL) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - CUT 8 Bit w/o PAL file: 2..256 Grayscales
   - CUT 8 Bit  /w PAL file: 2..256 Colors

  Writing:

   -  8 Bit as: 2..256     Colors CUT file plus PAL file
   - 24 Bit as: 2..256 Grayscales CUT file plus PAL file

  Remarks:
  ~~~~~~~~
  Note, that a Dr. Halo graphics always consists of two
  files with the following naming scheme:

    [name].CUT  => the graphics file
    [name].PAL  => the palette file

  During loading, only file names ending with .CUT
  are accepted and the corresponding .PAL file is
  searched automatically. If the .PAL file is missing,
  a grayscales palette will be used.

  During saving, the given filename will automatically
  expanded with the extension .CUT and .PAL - a .PAL
  is always saved (even for grayscaled graphics).

  Note, that 24 bit images always are exported
  as 8 bit grayscaled images.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_FBM "FBM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  FBM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of FBM (*nix) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - FBM 8 Bit x 1 Plane:  2..256 Colors/256 Grayscales
   - FBM 8 Bit x 3 Planes: 24 bit

  Writing:

   - FBM 8 Bit x 1 Plane:  2..256 Colors/256 Grayscales
   - FBM 8 Bit x 3 Planes: 24 bit

   Following to the specifications, a 2..128 color file takes as much
   space as a 256 color file: always 8 Bits are written.
   Only the colormap is sized differently for different colordepths.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_GIF "GIF.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  GIF.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of GIF87a and GIF89a files.

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   GIF 87a plain or tiled in 1..8 bit (plain) or 1..8/24 bit tiled
   GIF 87a anim first/last frame or tiled in 1..8/24 bit

   GIF 89a plain or tiled in 1..8 bit (plain) or 1..8/24 bit tiled
   GIF 89a anim first/last frame or tiled in 1..8/24 bit

  Writing:

   GIF 87a plain or tiled in 1..8 bit (plain) or 24 bit tiled
   GIF 89a plain or tiled in 1..8 bit (plain) or 24 bit tiled

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/GIF.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - GIF89A_TRANSPARENCY=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Transparent color (8 bit GIF89a) ?
                          ; default is: OFF
                        - GIF89A_TRANSPARENT_COLOR=<0..255>
                          ; Transparent color index (8 bit GIF89a)
                          ; default is: 0
                        - SAVE_INTERLACED=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Save interlaced GIF (8 bit) ?
                          ; default is: OFF
                        - ANIM_LOADING=<FIRST|LAST|ALL>
                          ; Load first, last or all tiles?
                          ; default is: FIRST
                        - TILED_LOADING=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Tiled loading (anims/tiles and 24 bit) ?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - TILE_NUMBER=<0..n>
                          ; Number of tile (0..n) - for TILED_LOADING=OFF
                          ; default is: 0
                        - TILED_LOADING=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Tiled saving (24 bit as tiled) ?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - LOCALCOLORMAP=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Save local colormap (8 bit)?
                          ; default is: ON

  Remarks:
  ~~~~~~~~
  (Reading)

    With GIF 89a transparency information is imported for all kinds
    of images (single, tiled, anim, 8/24 bit) but it depends on the
    output format whether a single transparent color, an alpha map
    or a real alpha channel is returned.

    There is auto-detection for "true-color" GIFs which are tiled
    images with different palette for each tile - in this case,
    the whole image is returned as 24 bit and the different
    transparency information results in an alpha channel. If the
    palettes are not different, instead an alpha map for an 8 bit
    image (like for PNG) is returned, consisting of multiple
    transparent colors. In all other cases max. 1 single transparent
    color is returned.

    Special code has been added which is able to distinct a tiled
    8/24 bit image in itself (same vs. different tile palettes)
    as well as against an 8/24 bit animation.

    In case such a file is detected to be an animation, the user
    may decide to treat it as tiled image anyway.

    This means, that the tiled file handling behaviour can also
    be overridden, in order not to load the whole GIF screen,
    but instead only a specific tile (like for TIFF page numbers).

  (Writing)

   Basically 24 bit writing support (in form of a 16x16 tiled
   image with different palette for each tile) can be turned
   off.

   Also, in addition to auto-recognition mode, a specific
   transparent color can be enforced for non 24 bit GIF89a
   output files. Note, that this will *override* any previously
   present transparent color (e.g. from a loaded PNG file);

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_Limbo "Limbo.sv5object"

  *** THIS ONE IS REALLY EXPERIMENTAL - IT WORKS, BUT REQUIRES
      A LOT OF MEMORY AND A FAST PROCESSOR.
      DO NOT SAVE IMPORTANT DATA AS LIMBO/LMB. IT'S HIGHLY LOSSY! ***


  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Limbo.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support and an installed
  Limbo 4.0 executeable.

  It supports importing Limbo 4.0 fractal-compressed bitmapped graphics.
  This is done by using Limbo for conversion of LMB files to temporary
  PNM files, which then will be parsed through sview5.library again.
  Exporting is supported by creating temporary PNM files, which then
  will be converted to LMB files via Limbo.
  A VMEM: assignment is needed to be present to allow doing the
  temporary file and directory management.

  So it supports reading and writing of Limbo 4.0 files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   (Limbo 4.0 fractal-compressed files, as far as supported by the
    used Limbo program.)

  Writing:

   (Any input will be converted to 24 Bit, which then will be converted
    to Limbo 4.0 fractal-compressed files, by the Limbo program.)

  Configuration
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  This Limbo support module has been tested with the Limbo 4.0
  port from Aminet:gfx/conv, which was based on a version developed
  by Carsten Frigaard, Jess Gade, Thomas Therp Hemmingsen and
  Torben Sand in 1993/94 on Aalborg University, Denmark.

  At first you have to install Limbo by simply copying it into a
  directory where you like it to reside.

  You also have to either supply an AmigaDOS search path to a directory,
  where the executable "Limbo.68000" is stored (default), or explicitely
  specify path plus name of the program by the controlpad entry
  LIMBO_PATH (see below).

  There's now also a PPC version available, which can be utilized
  when the LoadSegPatch of ppc.library has been installed (so that
  the ELF modules can be loaded and started as regular programs).


  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:gfx/conv/Limbo.lha        (68k version)
  Aminet:gfx/conv/PPCLimbo.lha     (PPC version; with LoadSegPatch, only)


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Limbo.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling Limbo,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 32768
                        - LIMBO_PATH=<Limbo command path plus name>
                          ; how Limbo is to be called
                          ; e.g. LIMBO_PATH=Work:Limbo/Limbo.68030.881
                          ; default is: Limbo.68000
                        - STATUS=<ENABLED|DISABLED>
                          ; allows to disable this module - for example
                          ; to be able to use an other, program-specific
                          ; import-module for the same file format
                          ;
                          ; DECODING settings
                          ; *****************
                        - DECODE_ITERATIONS=<number>
                          ; option -i of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 6
                        - EXPANSION_LEVEL=<number>
                          ; option -l of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 0
                        - DECODE_VERBOSE=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Should decoding output be sent to stdio ?
                          ; default is: OFF
                          ;
                          ; ENCODING settings
                          ; *****************
                        - EXPANSION_LEVEL=<number>
                          ; option -l of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 0
                        - MIN_RANGE_BLOCKSIZE=<number>
                          ; option -b of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 4
                        - DOMAIN_SLIDE_BLOCKSIZE=<number>
                          ; option -d of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 8
                        - MIN_COMPARE_DOMAIN_BLOCKS=<number>
                          ; option -m of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 4
                        - MAX_COMPARE_DOMAIN_BLOCKS=<number>
                          ; option -s of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 10
                        - FEATURE_SPACE_DIMS=<number>
                          ; option -f of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 3
                        - GRID_DIV_RES=<number>
                          ; option -r of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 1000
                        - QUADTREE_LEVEL=<number>
                          ; option -n of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 0
                        - TRESHOLD_SPLIT=<number>
                          ; option -Tm of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 100
                        - TRESHOLD_CLASS=<number>
                          ; option -Te of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: 50
                        - TRESHOLD_POST=<number>
                          ; option -Tp of Limbo 4.0
                          ; default is: -1
                        - ENCODE_VERBOSE=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Should encoding output be sent to stdio ?
                          ; (recommended, since endocing is
                          ; _extremely slow_)
                          ; default is: ON

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PAM "PAM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PAM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of PNM PAM (*nix) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   Most derivates of the PNM format will be read, including:

   - PAM P7 BLACKANDWHITE    1 bit Black & White (imported as 8 bit)
   - PAM P7 GRAY             8 bit Grayscale
   - PAM P7 RGB             24 bit TrueColor
   - PAM P7 RGB             48 bit TrueColor

     And the corresponding _ALPHA variants (with 8 bit alpha channel).

     If 16 bit data is encountered it is imported either as 48 bit
     for truecolor data or as 8 bit data for any other including
     alpha channels. If 4 bit data is encountered, it is scaled to 8 bit.

     If you encounter any unsupported files, please provide
     me with a sample for testing.

  Writing:

   - PAM P7 GRAY             8 bit Grayscale
   - PAM P7 RGB             24 bit TrueColor
   - PAM P7 RGB             48 bit TrueColor

     Writing graphics as binary 24/48 bit PAM data (P7 RGB) is the
     only way to prevent color information from getting lost.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/PAM.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - SUPPRESS_HEADER
                          ; setting this keyword will suppress
                          ; writing the PAM header for P7
                          ; files, which actually will generate
                          ; a RAW data file, which cannot be loaded
                          ; with sview5.library again, but may be
                          ; used for different purposes
                          ; Default: (not set)
                        - COLORDEPTH=<24/48>
                          ; Import/export 24 or 48 bit?
                          ; Default: 48
@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PNM "PNM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PNM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of PNM (*nix) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   Most derivates of the PNM format will be read,
   in ASCII (P1/P2/P3) and binary (P4/P5/P6) form.

   - PBM (P1)   1 bit Black & White (imported as 8 bit)
   - PGM (P2)   8 bit Grayscale
   - PPM (P3)  24 bit TrueColor
   - PPM (P3)  48 bit TrueColor

   - PBM (P4)   1 bit Black & White
   - PGM (P5)   8 bit Grayscale
   - PPM (P6)  24 bit TrueColor
   - PPM (P6)  48 bit TrueColor

   Note: Standard pixel max value is 255:

          - 65535 (16/48 bit) is only supported for P2/P3 and P5/P6,
            where it is either scaled down to 255 (8/24 bit);
            or for P3/P6 it may be imported unmodified as 65536 (48 bit)
            depending on configuration settings (default is 48 bit)
          - 16 (4 bit) is only supported for P3/P6,
            where it is scaled up to 255 (8 bit)
          - other values from 1..255 only supported for P2/P4
            where a proper grayscale palette is constructed

        If you encounter any unsupported files, please provide
        me with a sample for testing.

  Writing:

   - PGM (P5)  8 bit Grayscale
   - PPM (P6)  24 bit TrueColor
   - PPM (P6)  48 bit TrueColor

     Writing graphics as binary 24/48 bit PPM data (P6) is the
     only way to prevent color information from getting lost.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/PNM.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - SUPPRESS_HEADER
                          ; setting this keyword will suppress
                          ; writing the PNM header for P5/P6
                          ; files, which actually will generate
                          ; a RAW data file, which cannot be loaded
                          ; with sview5.library again, but may be
                          ; used for different purposes
                          ; Default: (not set)
                        - COLORDEPTH=<24/48>
                          ; Import/export 24 or 48 bit?
                          ; Default: 48

  Notes
  ~~~~~
  Writing the ascii formats P1-P3 (P2-P3) currently is not supported
  since they are considered to be slow and inefficient.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PFM "PFM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PFM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of Portable Floatmap HDR files,
  which are a floating-point version of PNM (PPM P6). The data
  format is comparable to the HDR Radiance format, but more
  precise. It consists of a truecolor (PF) and grayscale (Pf)
  variant.

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - PFM "PF" float bit import to  8 bit Grayscales
   - PFM "Pf" float bit import to 24 bit TrueColor  (binary  8:8:8   RGB)
   - PFM "Pf" float bit import to 48 bit TrueColor  (binary 16:16:16 RGB)

   By default, Pf images are imported as 48 bit, but this
   can be changed to 24 bit by preferences settings.

  Writing:

   - 8/24 bit export to PFM "PF" 48 Bit (as float)
   - 8/24 bit export to PFM "PF" 24 Bit (as float)
   - 8/24 bit export to PFM "Pf"  8 Bit gray

  Notes
  ~~~~~
   - PFM files are very different from normal raster graphics
   - therefore, the only reason to use the PFM format in
     a regular application is to interchange data with
     PFM-aware applications and/or to make the migration
     between pre- and post-processing of raw image data
   - in this context pre-processing means image capturing
     and mastering and post-processing means image display
     and rendering
   - on normal displays, PFM (HDR) files usually appear
     very dark, which is why some brightness adjustment
     is required in any case; this can be controlled
     by the corresponding controlpad
   - note, that during saving the input data gets modified
     (especially for "Pf") which may result in some kind
     of lossy behaviour

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/PFM.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - SCALE_FACTOR=<float value>
                          ; Linear brightness adjustment factor
                          ; Range:   16.0 - 1024.0
                          ; Default: 255.0
                        - COLORDEPTH=<24/48>
                          ; Import/export 24 or 48 bit?
                          ; Default: 48

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PNG "PNG.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PNG.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of Portable Network Graphics
  (PNG - pronounce it "PiNG", if you like ;-)  files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - 8 Bit color mapped files
   - any grayscaled images, 16 Bit derivates scaled down to 8 Bit
   - True color files (24/48 Bit, alpha channel ignored) as 24 bit
     or as 48 bit (so 48 Bit 16:16:16 optionally will be cut down
     to 24 Bit 8:8:8 - by default this is not the case)

     Thus the following types of PNG images (all valid ones) should
     be imported in the described way:

       Bit depths    Interpretation
       ----------------------------
       1,2,4,8,16    pixels are grayscaled samples

       8,16          pixels are R,G,B triple samples

       1,2,4,8       pixels are palette indices

  Writing:

   - 8 Bit color mapped files
   - True color files (24 Bit)
   - HDR files (48 Bit)


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/PNG.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - PNG8_TRANSPARENCY=<ON|OFF>
                          ; whether 8 Bit PNGs should contain
                          ; transparency information
                          ; Default: OFF
                        - PNG8_TRANSPARENT_COLOR=<0..255>
                          ; Default color to be enabled and set
                          ; (graphics control extension block)
                          ; Default: 0
                        - Z_COMPRESSION=<0..9>
                          ; allows changes in compression/speed.
                          ; 0 results in uncompressed data, 9 compresses
                          ; best, but increases decompression time.
                          ; Default: 6
                        - SAVE_INTERLACED=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Save image as interlaced (progressive) ?
                          ; Default: OFF
                        - COLORDEPTH=<24/48>
                          ; Import/export 24 or 48 bit?
                          ; Default: 24
                        - READ_EXIF=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Read EXIF data?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - WRITE_EXIF=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Write EXIF data?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - READ_IPTC=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Read IPTC data?
                          ; default is: ON

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PSD "PSD.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PSD.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of PSD (Ph*t*sh*p) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - PSD planar  1 bit b&w
   - PSD chunky  8 bit grayscale   (with optional alpha channel)
   - PSD chunky  8 bit colormapped (with optional alpha channel)
   - PSD RGB    24 bit             (with optional alpha channel)
   - PSD CMYK   32 bit             (8:8:8:8 CMYK as 8:8:8 RGB)

  Writing:

   - PSD chunky  8 bit colormapped (with optional alpha channel)
   - PSD RGB    24 bit             (with optional alpha channel)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PSP "PSP.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PSP.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of PSP (PaintSh*pPr*) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - PSD chunky  1 bit black & white
   - PSD chunky  4 bit grayscale/colormapped
   - PSD chunky  8 bit grayscale/colormapped
   - PSD RGB    24 bit

   Either uncompressed, RLE compressed or LZ77 (zip) compressed.

  Writing:

   - not yet supported

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_C64 "C64.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  C64.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of C64 Graphics files (Koala, Doodle, GEOS, 4BT).
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   Format    Dimensions            Colors

   Doodle    320x200               2/16
   Koala     160x200 -> 320x200    4/16
   GEOS      640x720               1
   GODOT/4BT 320x200               16

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_CDR "CDR.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  CDR.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support and BMP.sv5object
  to be present.

  It supports reading of the previews which may be part of CorelDraw
  .CDR files (e.g. with version 4) - these are related with plain
  Windows BMP files, so that CDR.sv5object will extract the graphics data,
  create a temporary file, write it as a BMP file and then parse it
  through sview5.library again.

  (See documentation of BMP.sv5object for which
   BMP derivates currently are supported).

  Reading:

   (Any contained preview, as long as the specific contained BMP derivate
    is supported by sview5.library).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_CVP "CVP.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  CVP.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of CVP (passphoto) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   24 bit CVP files (taken with a video camera, output done with
   a video printer, put onto a disk)

  Notes
  ~~~~~
  CVP files must have the extension ".CVP" and a size of exactly
  786432 bytes - otherwise they won't be recognized.

  Credits
  ~~~~~~~
  Thanks to Manfred Hoffmann for a sample CVP graphics and
  an arexx script that built the base for my own decoder.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_IMG "IMG.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  IMG.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bitplane-Support.

  It supports reading of IMG (GEM/XIMG) files like for example
  used with the Atari ST GEM desktop. Also the XIMG extension
  is supported. This may allow for exporting 24 bit images
  to Atari and re-importing them to 24 bit-aware GEM applications.

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - IMG (8/9 size header) grayscaled  (2..256 grayscales)
   - IMG (XIMG header)     colormapped (2..256 colors)
   - IMG (XIMG header)     truecolored (24 bit RGB)

  Writing:

   -  8/24 bit as IMG (16 byte header) grayscaled  (2..256)
   -  8 bit    as IMG (XIMG header)    colormapped (2..256)
   - 24 bit    as IMG (XIMG header)    truecolored (24 bit)

  Notes
  ~~~~~
  16 bit XIMG files are currently not supported.

  In general all non-XIMG files are loaded without colormap,
  but use grayscales instead - since the format itself does
  not contain any colormap in the HS 16 version - for the HS 18
  version there is also no clear specification for colormaps.

  In general, prior to saving plain IMG (non-XIMG) all input
  data is converted to grayscales since no palette can be
  stored in the output file. This results in 8 bit output
  data for 24 bit input data (256 grayscales).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_TIFF "TIFF.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  TIFF.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of TIFF-files (V5.0/V6.0/EP).
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

     Compression types (as far as known):

        - uncompressed       - CCITT Group 3 Fax
        - NeXT (2-bit RLE)   - CCITT/3 1D (Huffman RLE)
        - Mac PackBits       - CCITTRLEW (word-aligned uncompressed)
        - Thunderscan RLE    - JPEG (decompression not possible)
        - LZW                - zip

        ...and maybe more (converted to 32 Bit ARGB)

     Bit depths:

        Pixelbits      Planes      => resulting Bit Depth
        ------------------------------------------------------
           1             1            1
           1             x            x   (Mac Packbits only)
           4             3            12  (imported as 24 Bit)
           8             1            8   (256 colors or gray)
           8             3            24
           8             4            24  (24 Bit + alpha Channel)
          16             3            48
          16             4            64  (48 Bit + alpha Channel)

  Writing:

   TIFF can either be saved as V5.0, V6.0 or EP.

   Difference is the lack of IPTC/XMP/EXIF metadata in V5.0,
   some of this being added in V6.0 and again differing tag
   handling conventions in EP.

   Depth             written as
   ----------------------------------------------
   <= 256 colors     Motorola (MM), None,  8, 1
   (24/32 bit)       Motorola (MM), None,  8, 3/4
   (48/64 bit)       Motorola (MM), None, 16, 3/4

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
  Note, that due to the large variety of TIFF derivates out there
  (TIFF 5.0, 6.0, EP, EXIF, DNG, etc.) both - reader and writer -
  cannot be compliant to all of these specifications at the same
  time. E.g. there are some conflicting requirements for type and
  position of thumbnail images within these format flavours, which
  make it almost impossible to keep e.g. a thumbnail unmodified
  and at the same position when converting from EXIF to TIFF/EP.
  One format wants the thumbnail first, the other one later - one
  format allows JPEG for thumbnails, the other one not. Then one
  format has a different size restriction for thumbnails than the
  other one. Twisted. Better use PNG and XMP.

  Also, it currently cannot be guaranteed that all written - or
  appearantly written - information can be restored (and possibly
  rewritten) once again in exactly the same form.


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/TIFF.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - PAGENUMBER=<0..n>
                          ; number of image to be displayed
                          ; (e.g. for TIFFs with image directories
                          ;  or multi-page FAX documents)
                        - READ_EXIF=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Parse EXIF data during reading?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - WRITE_EXIF=<ON|OFF>
                          ; DESCRIPTION=Write EXIF data (specific tags, where supported)?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - READ_IPTC=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Parse IPTC data during reading?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - IS_EXIF=<TRUE|FALSE>
                          ; Is this a EXIF TIFF from inside raw JPEG APP1?
                          ; (set PAGENUMBER=1 for loading thumbnail)
                          ; default is: FALSE

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_EPS "EPS.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  EPS.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support and TIFF.sv5object
  (respectively GhostScript.sv5object) to be present.

  It allows two operations, depending on controlpad preferences settings:

   - extraction of the trailers/previews which may be part of EPS(F)
     files. This usually will be TIFF graphics, but it makes no matter,
     which file format actually is included, because EPS.sv5object will
     create a temporary file, which then will be parsed through
     sview5.library again.
     (See documentation of TIFF.sv5object for which
      TIFF derivates currently are supported).

   - extraction of the Postscript (TM) part of EPS(F) files, which then,
     in form of a temporary file, will be parsed through sview5.library
     (and perhaps also GhostScript.sv5object) again.

  Reading:

    - Any contained trailers/previews/thumbnails, as long as the specific
      contained file format - if any - is supported by sview5.library
    - Postscript (TM) as far as supported by the installed Ghostscript
      implementation

  Writing:

    - EPS files with Postscript (TM) image content, without TIFF header
      (only from 24 bit sources -> use the AnyTo24Bit operator).

      The graphics will NOT be vectorized - instead a bitmap-like
      representation of it will be translated into Postscript (TM) format.

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
  Please note, that the Encoding Routines of the Library are not (yet)
  fully re-entrant, so that only one Task may Encode a picture at a time.
  The Library itself manages it, that the other Task has to Delay() until
  the Encoding Routines are "free" again.


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/EPS.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - EXTRACTMODE=<HEADER|PS>
                          ; Determines, whether the preview image or
                          ; the Postscript (TM) part should be extracted,
                          ; while parsing the Postscript (TM) part requires
                          ; a working Ghostscript installation with
                          ; GhostScript.sv5object being correctly configured
                          ; default is: HEADER
                        - NO_EPS_HEADER
                          ; if this option is set, the EPS file will be
                          ; written without EPS header, thus turn into a
                          ; plain P*stscript file; useful for sending
                          ; it directly to the printer or for use with
                          ; FinalWriter, WordWorth, TurboPrint
                        - SAVE_ROTATE=<ON|OFF>
                          ; by default, the picture seems to be rotated
                          ; with Postscript (TM) output of this module.
                          ; Enabling SAVE_ROTATE will again re-rotate it to
                          ; the original position.
                          ; default is: OFF
                        - SAVE_CENTER=<ON|OFF>
                          ; centers the images on the page with the
                          ; desired size of SAVE_WIDTH x SAVE_HEIGHT (or not)
                          ; default is: ON
                        - SAVE_RLE=<ON|OFF>
                          ; allows to apply RLE compression to the
                          ; PS output
                          ; default is: OFF
                        - SAVE_DPI=<value>
                          ; DPI value to use for the output
                          ; default is: 300
                        - SAVE_WIDTH=<value>
                          ; Width of the PS page
                          ; default is: 612
                        - SAVE_HEIGHT=<value>
                          ; Width of the PS page
                          ; default is: 762

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_TIM "TIM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  TIM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of TIM (PSX) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   -  16 color TIM
   - 256 color TIM
   -  15 bit   TIM (imported as 24 bit)
   -  24 bit   TIM

  Disclaimer
  ~~~~~~~~~~
  Note: Only files with the extension ".TIM" will be recognized.

  Disclaimer
  ~~~~~~~~~~
  Since there - aren't any developer docs for TIM and PSX freely available,
                reverse engineering of the file format was the only possible way to
                support this graphics standard.

              - was no PSX available (and reading from original PSX CD-ROMs
                would have caused other legal problems), we did the complete
                programming and testing with an other third party program:
                PPaint 7.1 is able to read and write PSX graphic files.

  This made it possible to read and write TIM files without ever getting
  in touch with any PSX native, copyrighted stuff.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_GhostScript "GhostScript.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  GhostScript.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support and PNG.sv5object
  to be present.

  It supports importing Postscript (TM) language and PDF files as bitmapped
  graphics. This is done by using Ghostscript for conversion, giving
  a DPI resolution and a description code for one of the supported output
  file format, like e.g. PNG.

  GhostScript.sv5object will create a temporary file, which then will be
  parsed through sview5.library again.

  (See documentation of PNG.sv5object for which
   PNG derivates currently are supported).

  Reading:

   (Any Postscript (TM) and PDF files as long as readable for Ghostscript).


  Configuration
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  This Ghostscript support module has been tested with Rüdiger Hanke's
  AFPL Ghostscript 6.50r2 port from Aminet, which is
  Copyright (C) 1994, 1995, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000 Aladdin Enterprises,
  Menlo Park, California, U.S.A. All rights reserved.

  At first, Ghostscript must have been successfully installed,
  and working (test it via command line access).

  For enabling Ghostscript support, you either have to supply
  an AmigaDOS search path to a directory, where the executable
  "gs" is stored (default), or explicitely specify path and/or
  name of the program by the controlpad entry GS_PATH (see below).

  But as mentioned before, Ghostscript has to be installed and set-up first.

  Note: Using older Ghostscript versions than V6.50 may cause certain
        trouble, e.g. with the Fontmap or with emulators.

  Setting-up Ghostscript
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Since the documentation of some Ghostscript versions is anything-but-not-
  very-verbose I decided, to shortly explain here, what steps to
  perform to successfully install Ghostscript on your system:

      - unpack Ghostscript to where you wish it to be located at
        (e.g. "Work:Ghostscript/")
      - make an assign "Ghostscript:" to that Ghostscript directory
        (e.g. put the line "Assign Ghostscript: Work:Ghostscript"
         into your "S:User-Startup")
      - assign PSFonts: to your postscript font directory (anywhere)
        (e.g. put the line "Assign PSFonts: Work:Ghostscript/Fonts"
         into your "S:User-Startup", if that font directory already
         does exist there)
      - create some environment variables in ENV: _and_ ENVARC: which have
        to look as follows (respecting upper and lowercase):

           Variable          Content        Remark

           GS_FONTPATH                      *NOT* to be created (do delete)
           GS_LIB            PSFonts:
           GS_OPTIONS                       create, but leave *EMPTY* (blank)
           GS_DEVICE         amiga

         NOTE: There should _NOT_ be follow linefeeds after the content of
               GS_LIB and GS_DEVICE (!)

      - create a file "PSFonts:FONTMAP" with at least the following lines:

% fontmap aka Fontmap
% ----------------------------------------------------------------
/Times-Roman                    (putr.pfa)      ;
/Times-Italic                   (putri.pfa)     ;
/Times-Bold                     (putb.pfa)      ;
/Times-BoldItalic               (putbi.pfa)     ;

    The single ps fonts are assigned via the FONTMAP. For fonts used by ps
    files there must be an entry to allow interpretation of these files, but
    basically each font can easily substituted by an other.

    It does not matter, which font files are assigned for which fontname;
    in general entries within the FONTMAP file at "PSFonts:" just have to
    go conformeous with the following scheme:

          /Fontname             (Filename)      ;

    for example

          /Helvetica            (Helvet.pfb)    ;

    This means that the corresponding files must actually exist.
    But one also may substitute fonts symbolically by other fonts
    (to be understood like an alias or replacement font as known
    from Windows (TM) for "Arial" and "Helvetica") like for example:

          /Helvetica_Bold       /Helvetica      ;


  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - if special versions for specific CPUs do crash, then try versions
     for "smaller" CPUs (e.g. 68000 version instead of 040+FPU version).
   - please note, that setting DPI to higher values does not necessarily
     increase image quality, but memory usage (default is DPI=72).
     Same is to mention for the output colordepth:
     256 colors give better results, when you've to perform dithering.
   - files to be recognized must either have the standard Postscript (TM)
     header (containing '%!PS-Adobe' in it) or have the file extension
     ".ps" and begin with '%' (containing instructions for GhostScript).
   - PDF files are also supported (extension ".pdf" and beginning with '%'),
     but having the correct and needed fonts installed is more critical
     for these. Had not enough fonts to successfully test loading of any
     of these.
   - error output of Ghostscript still is directed to stdio/Output(),
     so problems may be visible transparently


  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:gfx/show/gs#?.lha  (#?=version, CPU and archive content)


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/GhostScript.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling Ghostscript,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 131072
                        - GS_PATH=<gs command path plus name>
                          ; how Ghostscript is to be called
                          ; e.g. GS_PATH=Ghostscript:gs
                          ; default is: gs
                        - OUTPUTMODE=<PNG256|PNG24BIT|OTHER>
                          ; Output file format to be used
                          ; (-sDEVICE parameter of Ghostscript's gs).
                          ; Only PNG supported yet.
                          ; default is: PNG256
                        - OTHER_OUTPUTMODE=<pcxmono|pcxgray|pcx16|pcx256|
                                            pcx24b|tiffcrle|tiff24nc|
                                            pngmono|pnggray|png16|png256|
                                            png16m|bmpmono|bmp16|bmp256|
                                            bmp16m>
                          ; If OUTPUTMODE=OTHER has been set, the string
                          ; specified here will directly be passed as
                          ; Ghostscript's "-sDEVICE" parameter
                          ; default is: png256
                        - DPI=<value>
                          ; DPI value to use for the converted output
                          ; (-r parameter of Ghostscript's gs)
                          ; default is: 72
                        - STATUS=<ENABLED|DISABLED>
                          ; allows to disable this module - for example
                          ; to be able to use an other, program-specific
                          ; import-module for the same file format

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PIC "Pictor.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Pictor.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of Pictor/PC Paint (PIC) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - Pictor v2.0 with 1, 2, 4, or 8 Bit colordepth
     (monochrome or with EGA or VGA palette).

  Writing:

   - Pictor v2.0 Uncompressed with 8 bit colordepth & VGA palette
   - Pictor v2.0 Packed       with 8 bit colordepth & VGA palette

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - a usual extension for Pictor files is .pic
   - sometimes packed files may be larger than uncompressed
   - since the compression of packed files is poor, there
     may occur an overflow of compression blocks;
     the SV5Object will not return an error in this
     case since most readers seem to be able to handle
     those files anyway
   - in such cases it may also happen (intentionally)
     that blocks are compressing more than one line
   - if you want to be on the safe side, write large files
     always uncompressed (e.g. starting from 320x240)
   - Pictor v1.0 and v1.5 files currently are rejected

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_MAC "MAC.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  MAC.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bitplane-Support.

  It supports reading of MAC (MacIntosh MacPaint) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - MAC black & white 576x720 (1 bit) - Packbits compressed

  Writing:

   - MAC black & white 576x720 (1 bit) - Packbits compressed (pseudo)

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
  MacPaint files, which are to be loaded into "MAC.sv5object" should contain
  the specific MacBinary Header (first the 128 Byte-Header, then the
  MacPaint specific data appended to it).
  In the PC area, there may sometimes files be found, which just contain
  the MacPaint 576x720 black and white Data.
  These files - without the header - can only be identified via the three
  leading zero bytes at the beginning of the 512 Byte MacPaint header.
  But there's never a 100% guarantee that a File with three leading zeroes
  really is a MacPaint File, so we also request a filename ending with
  ".mac" or ".MAC" in this special case.

  Remarks on Writing
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   - 24 bit input is not supported, since in most cases
     a semi-automatic pre-dithering to 8 bit will
     deliver better results (i.e. manual handling)
   - before writing, any kind of input files
     of wrong size (i.e. not 576x720) are scaled
     up/down using ScaleFree.svoperator
   - before writing, any kind of input files upto
     8 Bit colordepth are converted to 1 Bit
     black & white using HilbertDither256.svoperator
   - best results are achieved, if the input graphics
     is already of 1 bit depth (regardless if b&w or not)
     since in this case no dithering is applied, but
     only b&w palette matching and sorting

  The compression done during writing currently is a very
  inefficient pseudo compression only - this may change in future.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_MIFF "MIFF.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  MIFF.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,

  It supports writing of MIFF files.
  In detail these are:

  Writing:

   - MIFF 1..8 bit uncompressed, optionally with alpha map
   - MIFF   24 bit uncompressed, optionally with alpha channel (32 bit)
   - MIFF   48 bit uncompressed, optionally with alpha channel (64 bit)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_MSP "MSP.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  MSP.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bitplane-Support.

  It supports reading of MSP (MS Paint) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - MSP black & white (1 bit) - v1.0 (uncompressed)
   - MSP black & white (1 bit) - v2.0 (RLE compresed)

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - if MSP files are not recognized properly:

       - make sure, the filename ends with .msp
       - it is really a file from MS Paint and not a newstyle
         MS Patch file, which use the same extension under Win

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_MTV "MTV.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  MTV.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of MTV Raytracer files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - MTV 24 bit TrueColor (binary 8:8:8 RGB)

  Writing:

   - MTV 24 bit TrueColor (binary 8:8:8 RGB)

  Notes
  ~~~~~
   - if MTV files are not recognized properly:

       - make sure, the filename ends with .mtv
       - make sure the file really is in binary MTV
         format (only the first line is allowed to
         contain two numbers in ASCII format,
         separated by a space)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_NEO "NEO.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  NEO.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of Atari NEOchrome (NEO) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - res 1, uncompressed NEO 320x200, 16 colors
   - res 2, uncompressed NEO 640x200,  4 colors
   - res 3, uncompressed NEO 640x400,  2 colors

  The file extension needs to be .NEO.

  The filesize must be exactly 32128 bytes.
  A size of 17104 is also tolerated (even though not standard),
  which causes all missing bytes being assumed zero.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_MetaView "MetaView.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  MetaView.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support, a working
  ILBM.sv5object and an installed MetaView executeable with CLI interface.

  It supports importing WMF (also embedded in Win CLP), AMF, IFF-DR2D, IFF-DRSF, DXF
  and WPG vector drawings as bitmapped graphics. Optionally also FIG and CGM graphics
  may be handled through MetaView instead of using the default methods for CGM (@{"GPlot.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_GPlot })
  and FIG (@{"AmiFIG.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_AmiFIG }).

  This is done by using MetaView for conversion of WMF (Windows Meta File)
  or Windows CLP, AMF (Amiga Meta File), IFF-DR2D, IFF-DRSD (DrawStudio), DXF (CAD) or WPG
  vector files (optionally also FIG and CGM files) to IFF-ILBM files, which then will be
  parsed through sview5.library again using @{"ILBM.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_IFF-ILBM }.

  Reading:

   (Any WMF, Win CLP, AMF, IFF-DR2D, IFF-DRSD, DXF and WPG vector drawings (optionally
    also FIG and CGM) as long as understood and correctly converted to IFF-ILBM by MetaView)


  Configuration
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  This WMF/AMF/IFF-DR2D/DXF/WPG (plus FIG nad CGM) vector support module has been
  tested with: MetaView 2.0 (C) by Henk Jonas, which is Shareware (30 DEM/20 USD)
  and can be obtained from Aminet (see below). For some features, a newer version
  may be required, though (follow the homepage URL for a download link).

  Henk Jonas - eMail: subvcbhd@dattel.zrz.tu-berlin.de
               WWW:   http://www.cs.tu-berlin.de/~jonash

  At first, you have to correctly install and configure MetaView and
  the libraries it is using for vector graphics parsing.

  Also, you have to supply an AmigaDOS search path to a directory, where
  the executable "MetaView" is stored (default), or explicitely specify
  path plus name of the program by the controlpad entry METAVIEW_PATH
  (see below).


  Notes
  ~~~~~
  DXF and CLP files will only be recognized, if the file extensions have
  not been changed (.DXF and .CLP).


  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:gfx/conv/MetaView.lha


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/MetaView.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling MetaView,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 32768
                        - METAVIEW_PATH=<MetaView command path plus name>
                          ; how MetaView is to be called
                          ; e.g. METAVIEW_PATH=Work:AMF/MetaView
                          ; default is: MetaView
                        - FIG_SUPPORT
                          ; if this keyword is set, AmiFIG.sv5object will
                          ; be overriden and instead MetaView will be
                          ; utilized for imporint FIG drawings
                        - CGM_SUPPORT
                          ; if this keyword is set, GPlot.sv5object will
                          ; be overriden and instead MetaView will be
                          ; utilized for imporint CGM graphics
                        - STATUS=<ENABLED|DISABLED>
                          ; allows to disable this module - for example
                          ; to be able to use an other, program-specific
                          ; import-module for the same file format

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_SPP "SPP.sv5object"

  *** THIS ONE IS REALLY EXPERIMENTAL ***


  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  SPP.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support and an installed
  SPP 1.0x executeable.

  It supports importing/exporting SPP compressed bitmapped graphics.

  SPP implements SPIHT - image Compression with Set Partitioning in
  Hierachical Trees. It's a distributable version of SPIHT's compression
  software which does not include any patented or copyrighted algorithms/methods.

  Importing is done by using SPP for conversion of SPC files to temporary
  PNM files, which then will be parsed through sview5.library again.

  Exporting is supported by creating temporary PNM files, which then
  will be converted to SPC files via SPP.

  The VMEM: assignment is not utilized, instead the temporary files always
  will be written to the same path as the SPC files (this inhibits reading
  from read-only media; if anyone really should care about this, then please
  let me know). The temporary files will be deleted again after usage.

  Note, that every written file will get the .spc extension.
  The extension also is needed to identify SPP-compressed files,
  so don't remove it.

  So it supports reading and writing of SPP files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   (SPP-compressed .SPC files, as far as supported by the used SPP program.)

  Writing:

   (Any input needs to be supplied in 24 Bit, which then will be converted
    to SPP-compressed .SPC files, by the SPP program.)

  Configuration
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  This SPP support module has been tested with the Michael Cheng's
  SPP 1.09 port from Aminet:gfx/, which was based on a the version
  developed by Amir Said and William A. Pearlman in 1996.

  There's no special configuration needed, just install it and
  setup the contralpad options accordingly.


  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:gfx/conv/                 (please use the Aminet search)


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/SPP.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling SPP,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 32768
                        - SPP_PATH=<SPP command path plus name>
                          ; how SPP is to be called
                          ; e.g. SPP_PATH=Work:SPP/SPP-030-881
                          ; default is: SPP
                        - STATUS=<ENABLED|DISABLED>
                          ; allows to disable this module - for example
                          ; to be able to use an other, program-specific
                          ; import-module for the same file format
                        - LOSSY_FACTOR
                          ; 0..12, where 0 means non-lossy
                          ; default is: 0

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_RAS "SunRaster.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  SunRaster.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of SunRaster (RAS) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - SunRaster with   2 Colors ( 1 Bit, planar)
   - SunRaster with 256 Colors ( 8 Bit, chunky pixel)
   - SunRaster with  24 bit    (24 bit, R-G-B)

  Writing:

   Depending on the Colordepth of the source the following is written :

   Source Colors    Type                           Destination Colors

    2..256          Uncompressed Chunky Pixel        256
    (24 bit)        Uncompressed 24 bit RGB         (24 bit)

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - files with Colorbits other than 1, 8 or 24 are not supported yet
   - only RGB-planar colormaps supported (or monochrome, without map)
   - max. 1 plane of bitmap data allowed

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_SGI "SGI.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  SGI.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with 24 bit Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of SGI files.
  In detail these are:

   Colors  Depth  Organisation                   RLE-Compression

     256   8      8 Bit Chunky Pixel (gray)      supported
    (24  Bit)     8:8:8 24 bit RGB               supported
    (32  Bit)     8:8:8:8 32 bit RGBA            supported

   Loading and importing the (optional) alpha channel
   is supported.

  Writing:

   Source Colors    Type                        Destination Colors

   (24 bit)         Uncompressed RGB            (24 bit)

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - Currently files with BPC-Values of 2 are not supported, which
     means that pixel data has to be stored in bytes, not words
     (either gray 8 Bit or 24 bit RGB as 8:8:8, not 16 or 16:16:16)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_TARGA "Targa.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Targa.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of TGA (Truevision Targa) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   Colors  Depth  Organisation                   RLE-Compression

     1        1   planar monochrome              supported
     256      8   chunky pixel (colors/gray)     supported
     32768   16   "HighColor 15/16 Bit" Pixel    supported
      (24 bit)    BGR-Pixel                      supported
      (32 bit)    BGRA-Pixel                     supported

  Writing:

   Depending on the Colordepth of the source the following is written :

   Source Colors    Type                           Destination Colors

    2 .. 256        Uncompressed chunky pixel         256
    (24 bit)        Uncompressed BGR                 (24 bit)

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - PaintShop (3.0) and PaintShopPro (2.01) seem to write Targa
     files with a bad colormap (the same does apply to PixView 1.8,
     which perhaps was programmed using PaintShop files for testing).

     Corel PhotoPaint 4.0 crashed when opening one of these, PPaint 7.0
     and Targa.sv5object did import a strange gray palette instead
     of the real one. PaintShop(Pro) however seems to be able to read
     SView5-Library written Targa files correctly.

   - The flags for "mirroring" Images vertically and/or horizontally
     are not fully interpreted yet, nevertheless these will be reported
     by SVL_FileInfoRequest()
     If the VERTINV flag is not set, the picture will be assumed to
     be written as "from bottom to top", otherwise as "from top to
     bottom". Some programs do not set these flags right, when writing,
     so that you might get just the opposite result as expected.
     The HORIZINV flag is currently ignored: when reading such a picture
     as usual, you'd get a mirrored image. But this flag is also set
     wrong sometimes ...

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_UtahRLE "UtahRLE.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  UtahRLE.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of URT (RLE.5) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - UtahRLE 8 Bit x 1 Channel:  256 Grayscales
   - UtahRLE 8 Bit x 3 Channels: 24 bit

  Writing:

   - UtahRLE 8 Bit x 3 Channels: 24 bit

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
  Color maps: Reading/writing of color maps is not supported,
  except for the single background color. Reason is, that URT
  follows quite a strange conceptual approach here, and it
  was not considered worth the effort implementing it. If you
  need Gamma correction, better convert your images to PNG.

  Orientation: For some reason, all URT images which I've
  tested, were upside down, i.e. rotated by 180 degrees.
  Since this effect is not described in the specification,
  it is not clear why this happens and whether it is really
  the case with all images (even if not written by the
  original toolkit). For this reason, all images are
  rotated (again) after reading / before writing, unless
  you turn this off in the preferences (done using
  Rotate.sv5operator).

  Alpha channel: If the image contains an alpha channel (thus
  4 color channels) it will be imported along with the image.
  Saving is not yet supported.

  Compression: When saving, there's no compression performed
  at all. The image is RLE.5 encoded, but only makes use
  of Byte Data (i.e. one per line) but not Run Data ops.

  Compliance: The decoder has been tested with the 5 sample
  images included in the URT package (all 24 bit), the
  auto-generated clock.rle (8/24 bit) and some more.

  General: The RLE.5 decoder and associated code has been
  implemented from scratch, following the specification
  from URT. Since there's room for interpretation, it might
  not behave exactly the same way in case some image does
  not exactly follow the specifications/conventions.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/UtahRLE.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - NO_ROTATE
                          ; do not rotate images on load/save

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PICT "PICT.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PICT.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of Mac PICT v1/v2 Metafile graphics.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - Mac PICT v1/v2 with 1, 2, 4 or 8 bit colordepth
   - Mac PICT v2 32 bit  RGB (as 24 bit)
   - Mac PICT v2 32 bit ARGB (as 24 bit plus alpha channel)
   - Mac PICT v2 JPEG (JFIF) container

   All files are imported as 24 bit files currently,
   except JPEG which depends on the JPEG.sv5object
   settings (usually also 24 bit).

  Write :

   - Mac PICT v2  8 bit      ( 8 bit chunky always)
   - Mac PICT v2 24 bit  RGB (32 bit w/o alpha channel)
   - Mac PICT v2 32 bit RGBA (32 bit  /w alpha channel)

   All files are written compressed (using PackBits).

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - the file extension has to be ".pct" (as on PCs), ".pic"
     or ".pict", otherwise it will be rejected
     (there do more checks take place, but those are less relieable)
   - in addition to that, more checks are applied;
     unknown compression types etc. might be rejected
   - note, that the ".pic" extension usually is used for
     @{"Pictor/PC Paint" LINK SVOBJECT_PIC } files, not for PICT files
   - font handling always will operate with the internal
     standard font instead of the appropriate ones
     (derived from PBM package, see Credits)
   - note, that not all image processing programs can
     flawlessly import all PICT v2 files (sometimes they
     just fail reading them depending on width/height)
   - note, that not all image processing programs can
     read 24 bit or 32 bit files; at least however
     P*intSh*p and Ph*t*shop usually manage to load
     them (however only Ph*t*shop may recognize the
     alpha channel, and still sometimes fails in V6)
   - note, that if you save a 24 bit file without alpha
     channel as RGBA all the alpha channel bytes are
     set to 0xFF (which is assumed to be opaque)

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/PICT.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - WRITE_ARGB
                          ; Write 32 Bit ARGB instead of 24 Bit RGB?
                          ; Default: (not set)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_JPEG "JPEG.sv5object"

  *** This software is based in part on the work of the Independent JPEG Group. ***

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  JPEG.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of JFIF files as written by
  "The Independent JPEG Group's JPEG Software" (release 6)
  and in addition SPIFF files as specified by ITU.

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - JPEG (IJG-JFIF), with output in 256 Colors or 24 bit
   - JPEG (SPIFF),    with output in 256 Colors or 24 bit

  Writing:

   - JPEG (IJG-JFIF), from upto 8 or 24 bit Input
   - JPEG (SPIFF),    from upto 8 or 24 bit Input

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
  * Writing JPEG files (JFIF and SPIFF):
  * Note, that JPEG-compression is lossy, which means that the original
    picture cannot be reconstructed totally.
    Only JPEG-compress files, of which you have backups, or files which
    you never want to edit and enhance again.
    You should always control the results from saving an JPEG-File : in
    some special cases (e.g. many thin lines on the screen) there may
    occur strong differences to the original picture.

  * Writing SPIFF files :
  * Note, that - due to the fact that SPIFF is not widely supported -
    JPEG.sv5object does not write any particular additional metadata
    into the SPIFF file which would not be present in a JFIF, either.
    It is mainly the container (header) which differs. Also note, that
    Note that the SPIFF files written by JPEG.sv5object violate the JFIF
    specification by not writing an APP0 marker that immediately follows
    the SOI marker - most JFIF decoders will be able to decode those
    files anyway, though.

  * Reading SPIFF files :
  * Any kind of JPEG file that includes an APP8 marker will be considered
    to be a SPIFF. Since this information is not used anywhere, it will
    not do any harm even if someone in the future should use APP8 for
    something different.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/JPEG.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands :   ;
                          ; STANDARD settings
                          ; *****************
                        - READ_MODE=<IMAGE|THUMBNAIL
                          ; Read image or thumbnail (e.g. with EXIF)?
                          ; Disables SCALING for thumbnail, returns
                          ; standard image (eventually scaled) if no
                          ; thumbnail present.
                          ; default: IMAGE
                        - COLORDEPTH=<8|24>
                          ; For READING colored 24 bit images:
                          ; should the output be done as 8 or 24 bit Data ?
                          ; default is 24 Bit data. Grayscaled graphics
                          ; will _always_ be exported as 8 Bit
                          ; default: 24
                        - QUANTIZATION=<0..100>
                          ; For WRITING 8/24 bit images as 24 bit JPEG:
                          ; 0   - poor quality, big compression
                          ; 100 - best quality, no compression
                          ; never use such extreme values, but try
                          ; something like 20, 50, 75
                          ; default is: 75)
                        - READ_EXIF=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Read EXIF data?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - WRITE_EXIF=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Write EXIF data?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - READ_IPTC=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Read IPTC data?
                          ; default is: ON
                          ;
                          ; ADVANCED settings
                          ; *****************
                        - FORCE_GRAY_DECODE
                          ; For READING images:
                          ; this switch overrides the selected depth
                          ; for colored images and always exports them
                          ; as 8 Bit grayscaled pictures
                          ; default is: not set
                        - DECODE_METHOD=<FAST_INTEGER|SLOW_INTEGER|
                                         FLOATING_POINT>
                          ; For READING images:
                          ; how to DECODE the 24 bit or gray data
                          ; default is: FAST_INTEGER
                        - DITHERMODE=<DITHER_FLOYD-STEINBERG|
                                      NO_DITHERING|DITHER_ORDERED>
                          ; For READING and dithering 24 bit images
                          ; to 8 Bit images:
                          ; how and whether to DITHER the 24 bit data
                          ; default is: DITHER_FLOYD-STEINBERG
                        - COLOR_QUANTIZING=<FAST|SLOW>
                          ; For READING and dithering 24 bit images
                          ; to 8 Bit images:
                          ; whether to QUANTIZE the 24 bit data within
                          ; two passes (not with DITHER_ORDERED)
                          ; default is: SLOW
                        - UPSAMPLING=<ON|OFF>
                          ; For READING and dithering 24 bit images
                          ; to 8 Bit images:
                          ; whether to do fancy upsampling on the 24 bit
                          ; default is: ON
                        - FORCE_GRAY_ENCODE
                          ; For WRITING images:
                          ; this switch causes grayscales to be written
                          ; no matter, whether the input was colored
                          ; default is: not set
                        - ENCODE_METHOD=<FAST_INTEGER|SLOW_INTEGER|
                                         FLOATING_POINT|FASTEST_INTEGER>
                          ; For WRITING images:
                          ; how to ENCODE the 24 bit or gray data
                          ; default is: FAST_INTEGER
                        - OPTIMIZE=<ON|OFF>
                          ; For WRITING 24 bit images:
                          ; whether to optimize the generated huffman
                          ; code (good compression, but slow)
                          ; default is: OFF
                        - PROGRESSIVE=<ON|OFF>
                          ; For WRITING 24 bit images:
                          ; whether to write progressive JPEG files
                          ; default is: OFF

                          ; HIGHLY ADVANCED settings
                          ; ************************
                          ; 3 more settings for scaling & threshold

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_LJPG "LJPG.sv5object"

  *** This software is based in part on the work of the Independent JPEG Group. ***
  *** This software is based in part on "ljpgtopnm" (see "Credits").            ***

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  LJPG.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of lossless JPEG files (LJPG format).

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - JPEG (LJPG), in 256 (1 channel) grayscales or 24 bit (3 channels)
     only 8 bit precision supported

  Writing:

   - JPEG (LJPG), only 24 bit input currently supported

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_JPEG2000 "JPEG2000.sv5object"

  *** This software is based in part on JasPer. ***

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  JPEG2000.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of JPEG200 files as covered
  by the JasPer package.

  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - JPEG2000, with output in 256 Colors or 24 bit

  Writing:

   - JPEG2000, from upto 8 or 24 bit Input

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/JPEG2000.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands :   ;
                        - JAS_JP2_ENC_OPTS=<key=value key=value ...>
                          ; JP2 encoder options (Jasper syntax)
                        - JAS_PGX_ENC_OPTS=<key=value key=value ...>
                          ; PGX encoder options (Jasper syntax)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PCD "PCD.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PCD.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with 24 bit Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of the unpacked resolutions of PCD-files,
  as BASE/16 (192x128), BASE/4 (384x256) and BASE (768x512)
  directly, and additionally BASE*4 (1536x1024) and BASE*16 (3072x2048)
  via the external NetPBM-tool "hpcdtoppm".

  It does not read the BASE*4 (1536x1024) and BASE*16 (3072x2048)
  resolutions directly, since these are encrypted in a way, which is
  not only undocumented, but also copyrighted by Kodak, who are
  taking a license fee for their decoding algorithms.

  Legal Issues
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  This program module is FREEWARE.
  The author does not claim any copyrights on the code, which is
  used to decode the YUV-data fromout the PCD-file (see credits)
  or on the other PCD-related information.
  Copyright is only claimed for the program as a whole, which means
  that some parts of the library module, which are also used within
  other SV5Objects, are copyrighted by the author.

  If the writing or the publication of this program should ever
  be considered to be partly any kind of a violation of third party
  copyrights, it is hereby expressed that the usage of this program
  is only allowed, if any user of it agrees to the following:
  If the case as described above takes place, any user has to
  delete any copies of this program immediately when he gets informed
  about it.

  Configuration
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  "hpcdtoppm" does not need to be configured. Just copy it somewhere.

  Where to DOWNLOAD from
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Aminet:gfx/pbm/#?.lha  (#? something with "hpcd" in it)

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/PCD.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - OUTPUTFORMAT=<BASE/16 | BASE/4 | BASE
                                      | BASE*4  | BASE*16>
                          ; specifies the output resolution to be used
                          ; default: BASE
                        - EXTERNAL_DECODER=<ABOVE_BASE|ALWAYS>
                          ; Use external decoder when?
                          ; default: ABOVE_BASE
                        - HPCDTOPPM_PATH=<hpcdtoppm command path plus name>
                          ; how NetPBM's hpcdtoppm is to be called
                          ; e.g. HPCDTOPPM_PATH=Work:NetPBM/ppm/hpcdtoppm

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_PXR "PXR.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PXR.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with 24 bit Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of PXR (P*xar) rendering files.
  In detail these are:

   Colors Depth  Organisation                   Compression

    (24  Bit)    8:8:8 24 bit RGB               none
    (32  Bit)    8:8:8:8 32 bit RGBA            none

   Loading and importing the (optional) alpha channel
   is supported.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_YUVN "YUVN.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  YUVN.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with 24 bit Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of IFF-YUVN (YUVN) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - IFF-YUVN 24 bit (gray, 411, 422, 444, 211, 222)
     optionally with alpha channel (DATA/DATO chunk)

     Gray will be imported as 24 bit with R=G=B.
     Use "ExtractGrayScales" operator to reduce
     memory usage - and redundancy

  Writing:

   - IFF-YUVN 24 bit (411)
     optionally with alpha channel (DATO chunk)

  Reading/writing from/to ClipBoard is supported.

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - only 24 bit sources will be written as IFF-YUVN.
     256 color graphics are NOT automatically transformed to 24 bit,
     so that you may have to use the "AnyTo24Bit" operator before saving.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/YUVN.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - READ_ALPHA=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Read alpha channel (DATA/DATO)?
                          ; default is: ON
                        - WRITE_ALPHA=<ON|OFF>
                          ; Write alpha channel (DATO)?
                          ; default is: ON

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_DEEP "DEEP.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  DEEP.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with 24 bit Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of specific IFF-DEEP (DEEP) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - uncompressed:     24 bit RGB  8:8:8
                       32 bit RGBA 8:8:8:4     (Alpha expanded to 8 bit)
                       32 bit RGBA 8:8:8:8
                       48 bit RGBA 16:16:16
                       64 bit RGBA 16:16:16:16

   - RLE-compressed:   24 bit RGB  8:8:8
                       32 bit RGBA 8:8:8:4     (Alpha expanded to 8 bit)
                       32 bit RGBA 8:8:8:8
                       48 bit RGBA 16:16:16
                       64 bit RGBA 16:16:16:16

   - DELTA-compressed: 24 bit RGB  8:8:8
                       32 bit RGBA 8:8:8:4     (Alpha expanded to 8 bit)
                       32 bit RGBA 8:8:8:8
                       48 bit RGBA 16:16:16
                       64 bit RGBA 16:16:16:16

  Writing:

   - uncompressed:     24 bit RGB  8:8:8
                       32 bit RGBA 8:8:8:8
                       48 bit RGBA 16:16:16
                       64 bit RGBA 16:16:16:16

  Reading/writing from/to ClipBoard is supported.

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - only 24/32 or 48/64bit sources will be written as IFF-DEEP.
   - there's no conversion done from e.g. 256 Colors to 24 bit
     to perform the requirements of this file format.
   - other compression methods (e.g. Huffman) are not yet supported
     due to a lack of information on implementation details
   - DELTA compression is equivalent to TVPaint TVDC compression
   - 32 bit TVPaint files with channel type 17 not yet supported
   - channel bit depths other than 8/16 (or 4 for alpha with 8 bit)
     not yet supported

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_FAXX "FAXX.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  FAXX.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bitplane-Support.

  It supports reading of IFF-FAXX (GPFax) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - IFF-FAXX 1 bit black & white, compressed

  Reading from ClipBoard is supported.


  Notes
  ~~~~~
  Note, that only IFF-FAXX files compliant to the official FAXX
  (Facsimile image FORM) as registered at CATS 11/13/91
  by Christopher E. Darsch (Atlantis Design Group, Inc.) are
  supported. These files do consist of the three chunks FXHD,
  PAGE and FLOG and may be extended by the GPHD chunk as defined
  by GPSoftware.

  NOT supported are the completely incompatible (and obviously
  non-standard) files as written by MultiFax, which seem to
  mainly consist of text and also may include an attached
  IFF-FTXT file. MultiFax, as a second option, also seems to
  output partly standard-compliant files, which in theory
  should be read correctly - in practice there did occur
  some problems with garbaged output though (yet it's not clear,
  whether it's the fault of the MultiFax encoder or our decoder).

  A typical file written by GPFax may look like this:

    FORM  FAXX
      FXHD
      GPHD
      PAGE

  A supported MultiFax file may look like this:

    FORM  FAXX   (19102 data bytes)
      FXHD
      PCON
      PAGE

  A non-supported MultiFax file may look like this:

    FORM  FAXX
      TELE
      CNFG
      PFLG
      FDSC
    FORM  FTXT
      MCMD
      MCMD
      MCMD
      MCMD
      CHRS


  Credits
  ~~~~~~~
  Thanks to Dr. Greg Perry (GPSoft) for help on implementation.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_RGB8 "RGB8.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  RGB8.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with 24 bit Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of IFF-RGB8 and IFF-RGBN
  (Turbo Silver, Imagine, ArtEffect) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - IFF-RGBN 12 bit RGB 4:4:4, RunLength4 compressed (Genlock bit ignored)
   - IFF-RGB8 24 bit RGB 8:8:8, RunLength4 compressed (Alpha channel ignored)

  Writing:

   - IFF-RGB8 24 bit RGB 8:8:8, RunLength4 compressed (no Alpha channel)

  Reading/writing from/to ClipBoard is supported.

  Reading an alpha channel is supported for 12/24 bit files,
  writing an alpha channel is supported for 24 bit files -
  however the "genlock" bit of RGBN/8 only allows for
  "boolean" alpha information to be preserved when saving:
  an alpha value of 0 means "genlock bit set" and
  a value of 1..255 means "genlock bit not set".


  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - only 24 bit sources will be written as IFF-RGB8.
     There's no conversion done from e.g. 256 Colors to 24 bit
     to perform the requirements of this file format.
   - other compression methods are not available, thus not supported...

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_RGFX "RGFX.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  RGFX.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with 8/24 bit Oneplane- and Bitplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of the new IFF-RGFX graphics file
  standard for AGA and RTG Amigas (see Aminet:dev/misc/IFF-RGFX.lha)
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - IFF-RGFX 1..64 bit uncompressed
   - IFF-RGFX 1..64 bit XPK-compressed (deprecated)
   - IFF-RGFX 1..64 bit ZIP-compressed

  Writing:

   - IFF-RGFX 1..64 bit uncompressed
   - IFF-RGFX 1..64 bit XPK-compressed (deprecated)
   - IFF-RGFX 1..64 bit ZIP-compressed

  Reading/writing from/to ClipBoard is supported.

  Reading/writing an alpha channel is supported for 24/48 bit files,
  resulting effectively in 32 Bit RGBA files (8:8:8:8) compliant
  to the alpha channel encoding commonly used (e.g. in PNG). For
  48 bit files, the alpha channel is written accordingly (16:16:16:16).

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/RGFX.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - PACKMETHOD=<xxxx>
                          ; XPK packer to be used for writing
                          ; "RGFX xpk-compressed" ("ZIP" if none given)
                          ; Default: NUKE
                        - Z_COMPRESSION=<0..9>
                          ; allows changes in compression/speed.
                          ; 0 results in uncompressed data, 9 compresses
                          ; best, but increases decompression time.
                          ; Default: 6
                        - SAVE_CHUNKY
                          ; forces chunky data to be saved,
                          ; even if source graphics was planar
                          ; (e.g. when converting from IFF-ILBM).
                          ; May also result in smaller files.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_QRT "QRT.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  QRT.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with 24 bit Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of QRT (POV RayTracer) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - QRT Dump 24 bit

  Writing:

   - QRT Dump 24 bit

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - only 24 bit sources will be written as QRT.
     There's no conversion done from e.g. 256 Colors to 24 bit
     to perform the requirements of this file format.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_RAW "RAW.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  RAW.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It is meant for primitive RAW data export, only.
  In detail the supported kinds of data are :

  Reading:

   - (intentionally not supported) (*)

   (*) see @{"RAW-IMPORT.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_RAWImport } instead

  Writing:

   RAW (LUT8):
     - 8 bit data (upto 256 colors) is dumped as bitplane without
       colormap by default; the default RAW format for LUT8 is
       similar to a non-interleaved AmigaOS standard bitplane
       *without* alignment
     - 8 bit data (upto 256 colors) may also be dumped as chunky
       buffer without colormap alternatively; the alternative
       RAW format for LUT8 is similar to CGfx LUT8

   RAW (RGB):
     - 24 bit data is saved as with * height 8 bit RGB triplets
     - 32 bit data is saved like 24 bit data with an additional
       width * height number of A(lpha) bytes attached
       (0 means fully transparent, 255 means fully opaque)
     - 48 bit data is saved as with * height 16 bit RGB triplets
     - 64 bit data is saved like 48 bit data with an additional
       width * height number of A(lpha) words attached
       (0 means fully transparent, 65535 means fully opaque)

   RAW Bayer Matrix:
     - 8 Bit Bayer Matrix (Camera CCD sensor data)

   RAW YCbCr16:
     - YCbCr16 data (Video Overlay)

   RAW RGB16:
     - RGB16 5:6:5 data (Framebuffer format w/o Alpha)

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - not that these files have no kind of file header,
     just plain RAW data

   - note, that 8 bit files are saved without colormap;
     if you need the colormap, use @{"RAW-CM.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_RAW-CM }

   - note, that the kind of content can only roughly be determined
     from the file size, and only in case width and height
     are known:

        file size <= width * height bytes     =>  8 bit planar       (**)
        file size == width * height bytes     =>  8 bit chunky       (**)
        file size == width * height bytes     =>  8 bit Bayer Matrix (**)
        file size == width * height * 2 bytes => 16 bit
        file size == width * height * 3 bytes => 24 bit
        file size == width * height * 4 bytes => 32 bit
        file size == width * height * 6 bytes => 48 bit
        file size == width * height * 8 bytes => 64 bit

     (**) ambiguous

   - in case of 8 bit files, the depth must either be
     known or calculated from the file size or
     calculated from the colormap size (cf. RAM-CM)
     (Bayer Matrix files have no colormap, though)

   - in order to make your life easier, however the
     file comment under AmigaDOS also contains the following
     information (you can check it from within CLI/Shell)

        NN bit (XXX), colordepth NN, NN x NN (width x height)

     where NN are place holders. XXX is either

      - "planes" (8 bit)
      - "chunky" (8 bit)
      - "RGB" (24 bit)
      - "RGB+A" (32 bit)
      - "RGB" (48 bit)
      - "RGB+A" (64 bit)
      - "Bayer Matrix" (8 bit)
      - "YCbCr16" (16 bit)
      - "RGB16" (16 bit)

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/RAW.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - LUT8_FORMAT=<PLANAR|CHUNKY>
                          ; Write 8 bit as bitmap or as chunky buffer?
                          ; default: PLANAR

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_RAW-CM "RAW-CM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  RAW-CM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It is meant for primitive RAW data export, only.
  In detail the supported kinds of data are :

  Reading:

   - (intentionally not supported)

  Writing:

   - 8 bit colormaps (as RGB triplets) with
     total size of file being a power of 2 (depth^2)
     multiplied by 3 (R,G,B)
   - optionally with lower 4 bit of (R,G,B) LUT8
     entries masked out

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - the color depth can be calculated from the file size

   - in order to make your life easier, however the
     file comment under AmigaDOS also contains the following
     information (you can check it from within CLI/Shell)

        8:8:8 RGB ColorMap, colordepth NN

     where NN is a place holder for the depth.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/RAW-CM.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - RGB_BITS=<4|8>
                          ; Mask out lower 4 bit of LUT8 entries?
                          ; default: 8

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_Unpack "Unpack.sv5object"

  Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  xpkmaster.library V2+ (GNU) for XPK/PP20 support
  gzip  (in search path)      for GZ       support
  bzip2 (in search path)      for BZ2      support

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Unpack.sv5object is an external Library-Module for the SView5-Library.

  This mainly is a placeholder SV5Object which does for you the work of
  explicitely unpacking files before working with them. The following
  compressions are supported:

        - GZ    (gzip  compression, via external gzip  command line tool)
        - BZ2   (bzip2 compression, via external bzip2 command line tool)
        - HQX   (Mac HQX format)
        - XPK   (XPK compressed file, via xpkmaster.library)
        - PP20K (PowerPacker compressed file, via xpkmaster.library)

  It supports reading of packed files and will re-parse these through
  sview5.library by creating a temporary, unpacked file at the location
  "VMEM:" and then retries the specific operation on the file.

  No write support (use SVG/RGFX instead, if you want XPK compression).

  Copyrights and Credits
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  The "xpkmaster.library" (part of the useful Xpk package, which can be
  found on Aminet) is developed under the concept of the GNU license by
  its authors (c/o Dirk Stöcker, stoecker@rcs.urz.tu-dresden.de).
  This freely distributable Library is needed by Unpack.sv5object,
  to decode and read XPK-packed files.

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
  * VMEM:
  * Temporary data will be written to a directory assigned to "VMEM:".

  * Compatibility:
  * This SV5Object is just thought to make your life easier, if you've
    to handle many packed files, which you don't want to unpack each time
    you want to display them.
    Nevertheless it is recommended instead to work with unpacked files,
    wherever possible.
    If you wish to pack files with PP20 or XPK, please use SView5's
    own SVG/RGFX file format for this purpose instead.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Unpack.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STATUS=<ENABLED|DISABLED>
                          ; allows to disable this module - for example
                          ; to be able to use an other, program-specific
                          ; import-module for the same file format

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_CSource "C-Source.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  C-Source.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library.

  It creates C or Assembler source code in chunky/RGB notation from any input graphics
  (<= 8 Bit and HAM as chunky, 24 bit as RGB).

  In detail these are:

  Writing:

   SRC C:       - 8 Bit as C-Source with UBYTE [] pixel array and UBYTE [][3] colormap
                  (HAM6/8 indicated by flag #define)
                - 24 bit as C-Source with UBYTE [][3] pixel array (RGB data)
                - 32 Bit alpha as ULONG[] array (ARGB data)

   SRC Asm 68k: - 8 Bit as asm source dc.b pixel array and dc.b (3-byte wise) colormap
                  (HAM6/8 indicated by EQU defined flag)
                - 24 bit as asm source dc.b pixel array (3-byte RGB data)
                - PhxAss, 68k and SAS/C ASM compatible (add section definitions manually)

   SRC Asm PPC: - like 68k Asm (GCC compatible)

   SRC Asm x86: - 1:1 like PPC Asm (GCC compatible)


  For simple extraction of a colormap from a graphics file, you should
  apply the Crop operator with parameters   CROP_LEFTEDGE=0
                                            CROP_TOPEDGE=0
                                            CROP_WIDTH=1
                                            CROP_HEIGHT=1
  and then save the result as C-Source.


  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - this module uses buffered I/O, but nevertheless is quite slow for
     larger graphics (I/O buffer is set to 64K for OS version >= 39)
   - usage of RAM-Disk for output buffers is strongly suggested
   - the module does raw output, which should be compileable with
     any Amiga C compiler - and any other compiler, when simply
     replacing

          #include <exec/types.h>

     with

          typedef unsigned char UBYTE;
          typedef unsigned long ULONG;

    - the "endmark" entries at the end of any written array may simply
      be removed; they actually have no meaning, but simplify the process
      of writing the data to the file (not included in width/height/depth)
    - at places, the endmarks also may facilitate alignment, e.g. with
      colormaps

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_WBMP "WBMP.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  WBMP.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bitplane-Support.

  It supports reading of WBMP (WAP Bitmap) files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - WAP Bitmap black & white (1 bit) - no compression

  Writing:

   - WAP Bitmap black & white (1 bit) - no compression

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
  The file extension needs to be ".wbmp" for proper recognition.

  Note, that for WBMP the white color is considered to be "transparent"
  by definition, which is why the transparency flag is always set for
  color #1 when importing a WBMP graphics using WBMP.sv5object.

  Remarks on Writing
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   - 24 bit input is not supported, since in most cases
     a semi-automatic pre-dithering to 8 bit will
     deliver better results (i.e. manual handling)
   - before writing, any kind of input files
     of wrong size (i.e. bigger than 255 in width or
     height, since 255x255 is maximum) are scaled
     down using ScaleFree.svoperator
   - before writing, any kind of input files upto
     8 Bit colordepth are converted to 1 Bit
     black & white using HilbertDither256.svoperator
   - best results are achieved, if the input graphics
     is already of 1 bit depth (regardless if b&w or not)
     since in this case no dithering is applied, but
     only b&w palette matching and sorting

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_WPG "WPG.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  WPG.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Bit-/Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading of WPG (WordPerfect) BitMap files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - WPG Bitmap v5.0/v5.1 (grayscaled)  with 1, 2, 4 or 8 bits colordepth
   - WPG Bitmap v5.0/v5.1  (colormapped) with 1, 2, 4 or 8 bits colordepth

  Writing:

   - upto 256 colors as WPG Bitmap v5.0 (8 bit colormapped)
   - upto 24 bit     as WPG Bitmap v5.1 (using 8 bi grayscale colormap)


  Remarks (reading)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  WordPerfect WPG files do not necessarily have to contain bitmap graphics,
  they also may contain various other data, e.g. vector graphics.
  If a WPG file contains a bitmap graphic in any of its chunks, it will
  be loaded, otherwise the file will be rejected - these rejected files
  may be loaded by a correctly configured and installed MetaView.sv5object,
  though.

  If a file does not contain any colormap, WPG.sv5object will
  generate grayscales by default.

  This version actually has been tested with graphics with 1, 4 and 8 Bit
  colordepth (2, 16 and 256 colors).

  Due to the fact, that the 2 bit-routine is identically to the 1 bit-
  routine you should not get any problems with those pictures.

  Remarks (writing)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Note, that any 24 bit input will be converted to 256 grayscales
  prior to saving. The grayscale definition will be explicitely
  saved as colormap along with the image.

  The saved bitmap is always in v5.0 format, since the difference
  is only marginal and v5.1 does not provide any additional benefit.

  The compression of saved files is intentionally poor currently
  - due to the special cases in the compression algorithm it
  was easier to do it this way in the first step.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_WinIcon "WinIcon.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  WinIcon.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading/writing of Win Icon files.
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - loading of Win16/32 icons now works
   - previously only subset (Win 3.x) worked
   - two new icon types (Win16/32)

  Writing:

   - Win16 and Win32 can be saved
   - if you save Win16, restrictions are
     slightly different
   - maximum size for Win32 is 256x256

  You e.g. can save "favicon.ico" files for your
  website. Those are mini-icons that represent
  your site within IE or Mozilla Firebird.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_XBM "XBM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  XBM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of X11 BitMap (XBM) files
  in version v10/v11 (which are somewhat different). Note,
  that with recent X11 systems only v11 is used.

  It is recommended to use XPM only for icon-style
  black & white images.

  In detail the supported versions are :

  Reading:

   - XPM v10 1 Bit raw C-source notation (int)
   - XPM v11 1 Bit raw C-source notation (char)

  Writing:

   - XPM v11 1 Bit raw C-source notation (char)
     (from upto 8 Bit sources)

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - before writing, any kind of input files upto
     8 Bit colordepth are converted to 1 Bit
     black & white using HilbertDither256.svoperator
   - if v10/v11 files are not recognized properly:

       - make sure, the filename ends with .xbm
       - make sure, the first lines start with either
         "#define" or "/* XBM" or "/*"

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_XPM "XPM.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  XPM.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of X11 PixMap (XPM) files
  in version v1/v2/v3 (which are entirely different). Note,
  that with recent X11 systems only v3 is used, and that
  v2 has only been in use during 1990/91 for maybe 6 months.

  It is recommended to use XPM only for icon-style images,
  although there are no real implicite limitations whatsoever.

  In detail the supported versions are :

  Reading:

   - XPM v1 8 Bit raw C-source notation
   - XPM v2 8 Bit source-neutral notation
   - XPM v3 8 Bit C-source notation with embedded syntax

  Writing:

   - XPM v1 8 Bit raw C-source notation
   - XPM v2 8 Bit source-neutral notation
   - XPM v3 8 Bit C-source notation with embedded syntax

   Note, that for graphics with a very large width it may
   happen that very long lines of C-source are generated.
   Many C compilers will fail to compile them. However
   it has been taken care that at least XPM.sv5object
   will be able to cope with the output.

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - 24 bit data not supported
   - color definitions are supported in hex or octal format,
     i.e. "#xxxxxx" or "#oooooooooooooooo"
   - if a color definition in hex/octal format is missing,
     color names will be checked according the following table
   - symbolic color names not supported
   - white/black mapping not supported
   - instead, if a color definition is present but not known
     (e.g. "light_cyan") a reasonable grayscale value will be
     generated following a determined algorithm
   - if a color definition is present but lacks useful
     information, it will be treated as "-undefined-"
   - if a color definition is defined as "none", it will
     be treated as transparent (i.e. the related regions
     have no color) with black being the background color
   - if there is more than one "none" color entry, only
     the last one is taken as transparent color
   - if v1 files are not recognized properly:

       - make sure, the filename ends with .xpm
       - make sure, the "format" define is in the first line
       - make sure, the next 4 non-empty lines do contain
         the other 4 defines

  Color Names
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  The following color names are known and used in case
  no explicite colors are defined using the "#xxxxxx" scheme:

   white    #FFFFFF
   silver   #C0C0C0
   gray     #808080
   black    #000000
   yellow   #FFFF00
   fuchsia  #FF00FF
   red      #FF0000
   maroon   #800000
   lime     #00FF00
   olive    #808000
   green    #008000
   purple   #800080
   aqua     #00FFFF
   teal     #008080
   blue     #0000FF
   navy     #000080

 In addition:

   none             => black (transparent)

 Internally also:

   -undefined-      => black

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOBJECT_XWD "XWD.sv5object"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  XWD.sv5object is an external library module for sview5.library,
  which needs any SV5Driver with Oneplane-Support.

  It supports reading and writing of X11 Windows Dump (XWD) files
  in Version 11 (Version 10 not supported).
  In detail these are:

  Reading:

   - XWD V11  8 Bit gray
   - XWD V11  8 Bit colormapped
   - XWD V11 24 Bit 8:8:8
   - XWD V11 32 Bit 0:8:8:8 as 24 bit

   For 32 Bit files, little and big endian and different RGB masks
   are supported. For the others this is not applicable.

  Writing:

   - (not supported)

  Remarks
  ~~~~~~~
   - 16 bit files not supported yet
   - only ZPixmap format supported yet
   - lots of exotic pixel configurations not supported
   - contains kludge for mis-declared 32 bit files

@ENDNODE

# **************************************************************************
# SV5Drivers
#

@NODE SVDRIVER_ECS "ECS.sv5driver"

  Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  - AMIGA with Old or Enhanced Chip Set (OCS/ECS)

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ECS.sv5driver is an external SV_GfxBuffer display module for
  sview5.library, which allows object-oriented displaying on
  ECS displays.


  This Driver supports the following :

  Dimensions        Depth         Type

  [ECS]             [ECS]         BITPLANE
  [ECS]             8/(24)        ONEPLANE    (Chunky Pixel)
  [ECS]             (48)          ONEPLANE    (as 24 bit)

  The 8-Bit mode will perhaps only work on ECS systems which have any
  Graphic Card installed, which allows 256 or more colors in a way
  of an Intuition emulation.
  24 bit Graphics will be displayed as "best guess of 256 colors"
  if no SV5Operator is specified.

  Autoscrolling of Screens larger than the actual display is supported :
  Just move the mouse to the boundings !


  Attention: if you get the error messages "this module can't handle HAM data"
             or something like that, you most likely have set 24BITOPERATOR
             to "24BitToHam", however the selected screenmode (e.g. by CyberGfx)
             doesn't support to display HAM data (HAM_KEY not set in MODE_ID).


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/ECS.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - 24BITOPERATOR=<OperatorName>
                          ; (case-sensitive, ".sv5operator" may be added)
                          ; e.g. "24BITOPERATOR=24BitToHAM.sv5operator"
                          ; or   "24BITOPERATOR=ExtractGrayScales"
                          ; specifies, which operation should be performed
                          ; on 24 bit graphics _before_ displaying them
                          ; (if not specified displaying will fail)
                        - 8BITOPERATOR=<OperatorName>
                          ; (case-sensitive, ".sv5operator" may be added)
                          ; e.g. "8BITOPERATOR=ExtractGrayScales"
                          ; specifies, which operation should be performed
                          ; on non-ECS graphics (more than 16 Colors in
                          ; HighRes, more than 32 Colors in LowRes, HAM8)
                          ; (if not specified, will be tried to display)
                        - BITMAPCOPY=<DIRECT|RTG>
                          ; "BITMAPCOPY=RTG" prevents ECS.sv5driver from
                          ; directly copying into Bitmaps, which will
                          ; result in a usage of more memory, but keeps it
                          ; working.
                          ; Default is "BITMAPCOPY=DIRECT".
                        - SCREENINFRONT
                          ; Put Screen to front _before_ the graphics
                          ; has been displayed (useful with GfxCards)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVDRIVER_AGA "AGA.sv5driver"

  Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  - OS V3+ (V39+) and its libraries (takes advantage of V40+)
  - AMIGA with AGA ChipSet (OCS/ECS still supported, but with restrictions)
    or an appropriate Graphics Card with Workbench Emulation

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  AGA.sv5driver is an external SV_GfxBuffer display module for
  sview5.library, which allows object-oriented displaying on
  AGA displays.


  This Driver supports the following :

  Dimensions        Depth         Type

  [AGA]             [AGA]         BITPLANE
  [AGA]             8/(24)        ONEPLANE    (Chunky Pixel)
  [AGA]             (48)          ONEPLANE    (as 24 bit)

  24 bit Graphics will be displayed as "best guess of 256 colors"
  if no SV5Operator is specified.

  Autoscrolling of Screens larger than the actual display is supported :
  Just move the mouse to the boundings !

  Attention: if you get the error messages "this module can't handle HAM data"
             or something like that, you most likely have set 24BITOPERATOR
             to "24BitToHam", however the selected screenmode (e.g. by CyberGfx)
             doesn't support to display HAM data (HAM_KEY not set in MODE_ID).


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/AGA.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - 24BITOPERATOR=<OperatorName>
                          ; (case-sensitive, ".sv5operator" may be added)
                          ; e.g. "24BITOPERATOR=24BitToHAM.sv5operator"
                          ; or   "24BITOPERATOR=ExtractGrayScales"
                          ; specifies, which operation should be performed
                          ; on 24 bit graphics _before_ displaying them
                          ; (if not specified, "best guess" colors will
                          ;  be used, which is really slow)
                        - BITMAPCOPY=<DIRECT|RTG>
                          ; "BITMAPCOPY=RTG" prevents AGA.sv5driver from
                          ; directly copying into Bitmaps, which will
                          ; result in a usage of more memory, but keeps it
                          ; working.
                          ; Default is "BITMAPCOPY=DIRECT".
                        - SCREENINFRONT
                          ; Put Screen to front _before_ the graphics
                          ; has been displayed (useful with GfxCards)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVDRIVER_Window "Window.sv5driver"

  Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
   @{"AGA" LINK SVDRIVER_AGA } and/or @{"CyberGraphX" LINK SVDRIVER_CyberGraphX } RTG system.

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Window.sv5driver is an external SV_GfxBuffer display module for
  sview5.library, which allows object-oriented displaying on
  AGA/RTG displays in a window on a selectable Intuition public screen.

  The driver adjusts itself to the given display - which means,
  that colors either are remapped to the given screen colors using
  a "best pen" algorithm (OS compliant) or - in case of a RTG
  24 bit screen - will be rendered in true color. Note, that
  48 bit input graphics will be rendered as 24 bit always.

  Scrolling within the window boundaries is possible, if the
  displayed graphics is larger than the original window size - if
  that is the case, the SV5Driver runs in a special scroll mode,
  which does not give the control back to the calling program
  until that mode ended.

  If the graphics completely fits into the window or the
  window - which is resizeable - afterwards became smaller
  than the graphics, the scroll mode will not be entered.

  When in scroll mode, the user may scroll the graphics into
  four directions using the cursor keys. Pressing the left
  mouse button or any other (vanilla) key ends the scroll mode
  and again gives control back to the calling application
  (usually another mouse click or special keyboard shortcut
  then will close the graphics window).

  The title bar of the display window states in which mode
  the SV5Driver currently is.


  Notes
  ~~~~~
  When scroll mode isn't turned on, there's no interaction
  between the SV5Driver and the calling program possible;
  so the possibility of resizing the window is disabled.
  Unfortunately, the normal window refresh (caused by
  window overlays) is disabled as well. You may wish
  to take a look at the "WinSlide" tool coming with
  SView5, which does not suffer from these problems.


  Credits
  ~~~~~~~
  Thanks to (in alphabetical order) Frank Dietrich, Sven Drieling,
  Tom Lively and several others for intensive beta testing.


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Window.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - 24BITOPERATOR=<OperatorName>
                          ; (case-sensitive, ".sv5operator" may be added)
                          ; e.g. "24BITOPERATOR=Dither24Bit.sv5operator"
                          ; or   "24BITOPERATOR=ExtractGrayScales"
                          ; specifies, which operation should be performed
                          ; on 24 bit graphics _before_ displaying them
                          ; on a screen with a colordepth <= 8
                          ; (if not specified, "best guess" colors will
                          ;  be used, which is really slow). Note, that
                          ; HAM is not allowed (thus don't specify the
                          ; 24BitToHAM operator).
                        - SCROLLSPEED=<Pixels>
                          ; determines, how many pixel should
                          ; be scrolled in any direction when
                          ; being in scroll mode and a cursor key
                          ; is pressed
                          ; Default: 10 (medium slow)
                        - PUBSCREEN_NAME=<PubScreenName>
                          ; where the window driver should open
                          ; its windows (if not set or not available,
                          ; the default Public Screen will be used).
                        - SCROLLMODE=<AUTO|NEVER|ALWAYS>
                          ; - 'ALWAYS' activates scroll mode even for
                          ; non-oversized graphics; this will block
                          ; the input of the calling program as
                          ; long as no key or mouse button has been
                          ; pressed inside the display window - but
                          ; will avoid window-refresh problems.
                          ; - 'NEVER' is to avoid the blocking of
                          ; input handling that is caused by the
                          ; scrolling handler
                          ; Default: AUTO
                        - TRUECOLOR8
                          ; if the Pubscreen is a 24 bit screen but
                          ; the graphics to be displayed is 'only'
                          ; 8 bit or HAM6/8, usually remapping is
                          ; done nevertheless. This option instead
                          ; allows to call "AnyTo24Bit" first,
                          ; thus giving better display quality
                          ; on 24 bit screens. This is memory
                          ; intensive, because for scrolling we
                          ; need another complete 24 bit buffer.
                          ; (requires AnyTo24Bit.sv5operator)
                        - PEN_PRECISION=<IMAGE|EXACT>
                          ; you should not change this
                          ; default: IMAGE
                        - REFRESHMODE=<SMART|SIMPLE>
                          ; window refresh mode
                          ; default: SMART

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVDRIVER_CgxOverlay "CgxOverlay.sv5driver"

  Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  @{"CyberGraphX" LINK SVDRIVER_CyberGraphX } RTG system, plus a graphics
  card that does support CyberGraphX' video/overlay feature (e.g. CyberVision64/3D).


  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  CgxOverlay.sv5driver is an external SV_GfxBuffer display module for
  sview5.library, which allows object-oriented displaying on
  RTG displays in an overlay window on a selectable Intuition public
  screen.

  When in overlay mode, a true color window (16 Bit) can be created on
  a given screen - the difference to a normal window just is, that a) the
  underlying screen does not need to have the same colordepth and b) nothing
  can be moved over this window (if do it, it won't be visible).

  The driver does not need to adjust itself to the given display - which
  means, that no dithering is needed, because always 16 bit true color
  data can be written to the output overlay window.

  Currently, no scrolling is possible - but the overlay window can
  be resized to fit (handled in hardware).

  Overlay Support: Background Information
  ---------------------------------------
  With an installed cgxvideo.library you can make use of the overlay
  feature of any graphics cards that supports overlay (through this
  library, that is).

  The CV64/3D supports video overlay, unless the driver's MULTIMEDIAMEM
  setting has been changed, so that the 1 MB of texture/overlay memory
  is being utilized for conventional display. One overlay "window"
  at a time is possible.

  With the BVision/PPC (which perhaps also applies to the CyberVision/PPC)
  it has been reported, that adding the tooltype VLAYER=DESTRUCTIVE
  to the BVision Monitor Driver will enable overlay support through
  cgxvideo.library, at least with CyberGraphX V4.1 (the commercial release).

  However, you need at least the V4.2 drivers for the needed RGB15/16PC
  overlay formats - thus BV/CV-PPC users do need at least V4.2 of CyberGraphX
  for fast overlay support. There's YCbCr16 overlay support as well, however
  it has huge memory requirements and does result in slower displaying
  (due to the unavoidable conversion overhead from 24 Bit RGB to YCbCr16).


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/CgxOverlay.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - PUBSCREEN_NAME=<PubScreenName>
                          ; where the window driver should open
                          ; its windows (if not set or not available,
                          ; the default Public Screen will be used).
                        - REFRESHMODE=<SMART|SIMPLE>
                          ; window refresh mode
                          ; default: SMART
                        - CLOSEGADGET=<YES|NO>
                          ; add a close gadget to the overlay window ?
                          ; default: NO

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVDRIVER_CyberGraphX "CyberGraphics.sv5driver"

  Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  - OS V3+ (V39)+ and its libraries
  - AMIGA with CyberGraphX V2/V3 System and appropriate Graphics Card
  - cybergraphics.library V40+

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  CyberGraphics.sv5driver is an external SV_GfxBuffer display module for
  sview5.library, which allows object-oriented displaying on
  Amigas with the 16/24 bit CyberGraphX RTG System.


  This Driver displays any 1..8 or 24/48 bit graphics via the CyberGraphX
  System. Graphics upto 256 Colors will be displayed via usual graphics
  routines, 24/48 bit graphics will be displayed via CyberGraphX
  in either 16 or 24 bit (16 Bit is default, because the unregistered
  version of CyberGraphX does not support more and I guess, that
  not yet all the users out there registered it already).

  HAM6/8 will be converted to 24 bit, which then will either be
  displayed as 16 or 24 bit. 48 bit is scaled down to 24 bit.

  The driver will not open any Screens in standard ECS/AGA modes,
  since it makes more sense to use AGA.sv5driver in such a case.
  If no CyberGraphX screenmode is specified, it will be generated,
  which is just the same effect like with an intelligent screen promoter.
  No ECS/AGA screenmodes will be passed through, since this is
  neither useful nor practicable on two Monitor systems or with
  single 31khZ-limited Monitors.


  Credits
  ~~~~~~~
  Thanks to Ingenieurbüro Helfrich, for supplying the PiccoloSD64 card
  (in the meantime using a CyberVision64/3D and CyberGraphX V3, BTW).

  The CyberGraphX Software of course is copyrighted by its authors,
  which is hereby expressesively respected in all points.


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Cybergraphics.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - EMUSCREENDEPTH=<16|24>
                          ; beginning depth for opening CyberGraphX Screens
                          ; Default is 16 Bit (which will also be tried
                          ; when opening of a 24 bit Screen fails)
                          ; This does not concern colordepths < 16 Bit,
                          ; except HAM6/8.
                        - SMALLSCREENS
                          ; unless this keyword is specified, it is not
                          ; tried to open screens smaller than 320x240

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVDRIVER_PICASSO96 "Picasso96.sv5driver"

  Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  - OS V3+ (V39)+ and its libraries
  - AMIGA with Picasso96 System and appropriate Graphics Card
  - Picasso96API.library V2+

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Picasso96.sv5driver is an external SV_GfxBuffer display module for
  sview5.library, which allows object-oriented displaying on
  Amigas with the Picasso96 RTG System.

  The related Picasso96 libraries are needed.

  This Driver supports the following :

  Source    Depth   Special Modes   Dimensions            Dest. Depth

  ONEPLANE  48      -               [ as 24 bit]              24
  ONEPLANE  8/24    HAM6, HAM8      [ Picasso-Dependent]  8 / 24
  BITPLANE  1..8    HAM6, HAM8      [ Picasso-Dependent]  8 / 24

  HAM6/8 will be converted to 24 bit, which then will either be
  displayed as 16 or 24 bit.
  24 bit will either be displayed in 16 or 24 bit.
  48 bit is scaled down to 24 bit.


  Credits
  ~~~~~~~
  Thanks to Tobias Abt and Alexander Kneer (Picasso 96 team) for
  developer support and beta-testing/debugging.

  The Picasso96 Emulation Software of course is copyrighted by
  it authors, c/o Tobias Abt and Alexander Kneer, which is hereby
  expressesively respected in all points.


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Picasso96.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - SMALLSCREENS
                          ; unless this keyword is specified, it is not
                          ; tried to open screens smaller than 320x240
                        - EMUSCREENDEPTH=<16|24>
                          ; beginning depth for opening Picasso96 Screens
                          ; Default is 24 bit (if opening fails, it is
                          ; also tried to open a 16 Bit Screen, then)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_24BitToHAM "24BitToHAM.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  24BitToHAM.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  24BitToHAM.sv5operator dithers 24 bit RGB graphics to HAM6/HAM8,
  either quick or well.

  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/24BitToHAM.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - DITHERMODE=< HAM6_QUICK|HAM6_WELL
                                      |HAM8_QUICK|HAM8_WELL>
                          ; specifies the HAM-Mode to be used and
                          ; the resulting speed/quality

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_AnyTo24Bit "AnyTo24Bit.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  AnyTo24Bit.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  AnyTo24Bit.sv5operator converts any input graphics into TrueColor
  RGB graphics with 24 bit.

  Input may be any (upto) 256 Color graphics or HAM6/HAM8 data,
  as well as 24/48 bit graphics. Alpha Channel is preserved.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_AnyTo48Bit "AnyTo48Bit.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  AnyTo48Bit.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  AnyTo48Bit.sv5operator converts any input graphics into TrueColor
  RGB graphics with 48 bit.

  Input may be any (upto) 256 Color graphics or HAM6/HAM8 data,
  as well as 24/48 bit graphics. Alpha Channel is preserved.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_Blur "Blur.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Blur.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  It applies a Blur style filter to a given graphics.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_CallPNM "CallPNM"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  CallPNM.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  This is not an operator in the common sense.

  Instead it is just an Interface to allow easy access to any external
  operators from the well known PBM package (distributed as NetPBM).

  When using this operator, the given GfxBuffer will be saved as
  a 24/48 bit PNM PPM (P6) file (8 Bit input is converted to 24 bit),
  after that the specified external NetPBM tool is called and its
  output is written into another temporary file which is again loaded
  by SView5-Library. Temporary files are placed in VMEM: and are
  deleted automatically.

  For alpha channel support it is required to explicitely enable
  usage of the new PNM PAM (P7) format instead of PPM (P6). This
  will fail with older NetPBM releases and thus is not enabled
  by default.

  Please note, that the whole internal construction of the operator
  is a little bit more complicated than usual, so that error messages
  may lead into the wrong direction in general. For example the
  following errors cannot be detected and/or distincted from other
  errors:
          - an external NetPBM tool does not support 48 bit (maxval 65535)
          - an external NetPBM tool does not support alpha (PAM format)
          - an external NetPBM tool does not understand a command line option
          - an external NetPBM tool lacks an additional command line option
          - an external NetPBM tool requires more than one source file
          - an external NetPBM tool does not support input format type PPM,
            but onlt PBM or PGM
          - an external NetPBM tool is not a filter but a conversion tool,
            i.e. does not support input files of type PNM at all

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/CallPNM.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - STACKSIZE=<value>
                          ; stacksize to be used for calling PNM program,
                          ; increasing may help on crashes
                          ; default is: 32768
                        - USE_PAM_FOR_ALPHA
                          ; setting this keyword will suppress
                          ; enforce usage of PNM PAM (P7) format
                          ; if the input graphics has an alpha
                          ; channel attached; note, that older NetPBM
                          ; versions cannot handle PAM format; not
                          ; setting this options strips the alpha
                          ; channel by usage of the backward-compatible
                          ; PNM PPM (P6) format which lacks alpha support
                          ; Default: (not set)
                        - NETPBM_PATH=<netpbm command path>
                          ; folder from where NetPBM is to be called
                          ; e.g. NETPBM_PATH=Work:NetPBM/
                          ; COMPATIBILITY ISSUE: if left empty, it
                          ; is assumed that the path is part of the
                          ; PNMCOMMAND setting
                          ; default is: <empty>
                        - COMMAND_FILE=<command file name>
                          ; separate file for command & options definition,
                          ; overriding global PNMCOMMAND/PNMOPTIONS
                          ; default: (not set)
                        - PNMCOMMAND=<PBM command path and name>
                          ; PNM command to be called
                          ; e.g. PNMCOMMAND=Work:NetPBM/pnm/pnmscale
                        - PNMOPTIONS=<Options>
                          ; Options for PNM command to be called
                          ; e.g. PNMOPTIONS=-xscale 2.0 -yscale 2.0

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_ChangePalette "ChangePalette.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ChangePalette.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  ChangePalette.sv5operator exchanges the palette of any colormapped input
  graphics with that of another graphics.
  Both should have the same depth (otherwise colors may be missing or discarded).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_Crop "Crop.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Crop.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  Crop.sv5operator may extract shapes of any size from any 2..256 Color
  or 24 bit graphics.
  Values for "LeftEdge", "TopEdge", "Width" and "Height", describing
  the crop box have to be supplied via ControlPad settings.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Crop.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - CROP_LEFTEDGE=<Value>
                          ; crop from x position
                          ; (will be adjusted, if >= source width)
                        - CROP_TOPEDGE=<Value>
                          ; crop from y position
                          ; (will be adjusted, if >= source height)
                        - CROP_WIDTH=<Value>
                          ; crop how many x pixels from leftedge
                          ; (will be adjusted, if too large)
                        - CROP_HEIGHT=<Value>
                          ; crop how many y pixels from topedge
                          ; (will be adjusted, if too large)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_Dither24Bit "Dither24Bit.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Dither24Bit.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  Dither24Bit.sv5operator dithers 24 bit RGB graphics to 256 Colors
  by default. Possible is also dithering to less colors (2..128),
  if specified via ControlPad-Settings.

  This module applies Heckbert's median cut and dithers
  using Floyd-Steinberg.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Dither24Bit.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - COLORDEPTH=<1..8>
                          ; specifies the colordepth of the dithering
                          ; output (1->2 Colors .. 8->256 Colors)
                        - DITHERMODE=<BESTPEN|DITHER_FLOYD-STEINBERG
                                      |ORDERED|BURKES>
                          ; whether to just select the best pen or
                          ; do Floyd-Steinberg pixel error adjustment

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_DitherFix24 "DitherFix24.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  DitherFix24.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  DitherFix24.sv5operator dithers 24 bit RGB graphics to 32..256 colors
  or 2..16 grayscales using a fixed palette (specifying a color depth
  equal to or less than 4 results in the latter).

  This module applies Heckbert's median cut and dithers
  using Floyd-Steinberg or by using a best pen algorithm.


  Palette for grayscaled images (16 colors):
  @{"CLICK HERE" LINK SVOPERATOR_DitherFix24_8Bit }

  Palette for color images (256 colors):
  @{"CLICK HERE" LINK SVOPERATOR_DitherFix24_24Bit }


  If a color depth results in less than 256 or less than 16 colors,
  only every 2nd (4th, 8th) color from the respective palette is
  taken, the rest is discarded (starting from color 0). The lowest
  palette entry is always set to { 0x00, 0x00, 0x00} (black),
  the highest is always set to {0xFF, 0xFF, 0xFF} (white).


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/DitherFix24.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - COLORDEPTH=<1..8>
                          ; specifies the colordepth of the dithering
                          ; output (1->2 Colors .. 8->256 Colors)
                        - DITHERMODE=<BESTPEN|DITHER_FLOYD-STEINBERG>
                          ; whether to just select the best pen or
                          ; do Floyd-Steinberg pixel error adjustment

                        - [ plus a few more undocumented options ]

@ENDNODE

