@NODE SVOPERATOR_ExtractGrayScales "ExtractGrayScales"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ExtractGrayScales.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  ExtractGrayScales.sv5operator modifies any supplied source SV_GfxBuffer
  in a way, that its colormap will be changed to reflect gray-scales
  (works with (upto) 256 Colors and 24 bit files).
  Output is done in input colordepth or 256 Colors by default (fastest).

  This is a sample SV5Operator for simple demonstration how to write one.
  It's simple, but effective.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/ExtractGrayScales.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - COLORDEPTH=<1..8>
                          ; specifies the colordepth of the grayscaled
                          ; output (1->2 Colors .. 8->256 Colors)
                        - QUICK
                          ; uses >>2, >>1, >>3 (*0.25, *0.5, *0.125)
                          ; instead of *0.3, *0.59, *0.11
                        - SORTED8BIT=<NONE|ASCENDING|DESCENDING>
                          ; specifies the sort order for the
                          ; destination grayscale color map
                          ; default: ASCENDING

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_ExtractRed "ExtractRed"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ExtractRed.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  ExtractRed.sv5operator modifies any supplied source SV_GfxBuffer
  in a way, that only the RED values of a picture will be extracted
  for creation of a new (upto) 256 Color graphics
  (works with (upto) 256 Colors and 24 bit files).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_ExtractGreen "ExtractGreen"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ExtractGreen.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  ExtractGreen.sv5operator modifies any supplied source SV_GfxBuffer
  in a way, that only the GREEN values of a picture will be extracted
  for creation of a new (upto) 256 Color graphics
  (works with (upto) 256 Colors and 24 bit files).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_ExtractBlue "ExtractBlue"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ExtractBlue.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  ExtractBlue.sv5operator modifies any supplied source SV_GfxBuffer
  in a way, that only the BLUE values of a picture will be extracted
  for creation of a new (upto) 256 Color graphics
  (works with (upto) 256 Colors and 24 bit files).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_FlipNibbles "FlipNibbles"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  FlipNibbles.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  FlipNibbles.sv5operator modifies any supplied source SV_GfxBuffer
  in a way, that the byte nibbles (half-bytes) of its pixel values/
  components are modified (swapped or exchanged) in certain ways.

  For 48 bit graphics, respectively the bytes are swapped/exchanged,
  i.e. 8:16 instead of 4:8 bits are subject to modification.

  This is especially useful if you are operating on images which
  have been saved with bogus colormap or bogus truecolor values.

  Options are as follows:

    - SWAP:        exchange [1][2] nibbles to [2][1]  (e.g. 0xAB -> 0xBA)
    - MINUS_LOW:   from [1][2] remove lower nibble    (e.g. 0xAB -> 0xA0)
    - MINUS_HIGH:  from [1][2] remove higher nibble   (e.g. 0xAB -> 0x0B)
    - SHIFT_LOW:   in [1][2] shift up lower nibble    (e.g. 0xAB -> 0xB0)
    - SHIFT_HIGH:  in [1][2] shift down higher nibble (e.g. 0xAB -> 0xA0)
    - DOUBLE_LOW:  turn [1][2] into [2][2]            (e.g. 0x0B -> 0xBB)
    - DOUBLE_HIGH: turn [1][2] into [1][1]            (e.g. 0xA0 -> 0xBB)

  Note, that the last two operations also can be achieved by (subsequent)
  multiplication/division by 16 - however here it happens only by masking
  and shifting.

  Note, that the operations take place either on the RGB components of
  the colormap (for 8 bit images) or on the single RGB pixels (for
  24 bit images). For 48 bit everything is the same except that
  0xAB (8 bit) is equivalent to 0xAABB (16 bit) here and so on.

  The output of the SV5Operator has the same colordepth as before,
  and an optional alpha channel remains unmodified.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/FlipNibbles.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - FLIPMODE=<SWAP|MINUS_LOW|MINUS_HIGH|SHIFT_LOW|SHIFT_HIGH|DOUBLE_LOW|DOUBLE_HIGH>
                          ; Operating mode (see documentation)
                          ; default: SWAP

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_HilbertDither256 "HilbertDither256.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  HilbertDither256.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  HilbertDither256.sv5operator modifies any supplied source SV_GfxBuffer in a
  way, that all supplied graphics with upto 256 Colors are dithered to
  Black & White graphics (2 Colors), as e.g. needed for desktop publishing
  or output on matrix printers.

  It uses the fractal Hilbert curve for getting best results in
  eliminating the resulting errors.

  As a side effect, the resulting picture will always have a width and
  height, which is divideable by 16 (graphics will be adjusted this way).

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/HilbertDither256.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - BACKGROUND=<BLACK|WHITE>
                          ; defines, which of the two colors will act
                          ; as background color. Useful e.g. for printing.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_Histogram "Histogram.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Histogram.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  It has two modes:

   - mode "color": counts the occurance of colors in 24/48 bit
     files and renders the result graphically (sorted by intensity)

   - mode "brightness": like a normal histogram, but rotated by 90 degrees
     (in order to make it fit better, the max. values are cut if necessary)

  Optionally it writes a textual result to an additional, user-specified
  file (as unsorted list of RGB colors plus color count).

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Histogram.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - HISTROGRAM_PATH=<external text file>
                          ; Store a textual histogram? Where?
                          ; default is: <N/A>
                        - MODE=<COLOR|BRIGHTNESS>
                          ; What to count and show in histogram?
                          ; default: BRIGHTNESS
                        - WIDTH=<value>
                          ; Brightness mode: Width of histogram page (rotated Y-Axis)
                          ; default: 100
                        - BACKCOLOR_VALUE=<Hex Value 0xRRGGBB>
                          ; Brightness mode: Background color VALUE in 0xRRGGBB format
                          ; default: 0x000000
                        - FORECOLOR_VALUE=<Hex Value 0xRRGGBB>
                          ; Brightness mode: Foreground color VALUE in 0xRRGGBB format
                          ; default: 0xFFFFFF

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_InvertColors256 "InvertColors256.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  InvertColors256.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  InvertColors256.sv5operator exchanges the palette entries of any colormapped
  input graphics with each other. This results in the colormap being in
  reverse order compared to before, i.e. the result is compareable to
  negation/complement in some cases.

  For example: when exchanging black+white in a b&w graphics, it becomes
  a w&b graphics.

  Note: the result sometimes may look similar to NegateColors, but does
        not necessarily have to! Also: the old "Complement" svoperator
        worked like "InvertColors256" for colormapped graphics, but like
        "NegateColors" for 24 bit graphics.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_LeftToRight "LeftToRight"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  LeftToRight.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  LeftToRight.sv5operator modifies any supplied source SV_GfxBuffer
  in a way, that it will be swapped from left to right (mirrored)
  (works with (upto) 256 Colors and 24 bit files).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_NegateColors "NegateColors.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  NegateColors.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  NegateColors.sv5operator exchanges the palette RGB entries of any colormapped
  input graphics - or the single pixel RGB values of a 24 bit graphics -
  with their complement. This results in the colormap becoming its own
  complement.

  Note: the result sometimes may look similar to InvertColors256, but does
        not necessarily have to! Also: the old "Complement" svoperator
        worked like "InvertColors256" for colormapped graphics, but like
        "NegateColors" for 24 bit graphics.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_OptimizePalette "OptimizePalette"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  OptimizePalette.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  OptimizePalette.sv5operator filters all unused colors out of a palette
  of a given graphics with upto 256 Colors
  (EHB, HAM6/8 and 24 bit graphics will be rejected).

  A new palette will be created - which also misses any duplicate color
  table entries - to which then the given graphics is remapped.

  This Operator may have three effects (plus combinations):

    a) none, if the palette already was or has been optimized
    b) only some black colors at the end of the color map, if
       removing of unused colors did not suffice to fall back to
       the next lower depth boundary
       (<= 256 to <= 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64 or 128)
    c) a reduced colordepth to one of the next lower depth boundaries
       (as described under b) if there've been a lot of actually
       unused colors
    d) combinations of b) and c)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_PagePrint "PagePrint.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PagePrint.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  PagePrint.sv5operator takes a list of file names, which is used
  to create a thumbnail overview page. All files must be graphics
  files in a format supported by sview5.library (8 or 24 bit).

  The size of each thumnail can be determined, as well as
  the foreground (text) and background colors (for the page
  as a whole and for the thumbmails). Thumbnails may get
  a border of given color.

  The namefile must be in ASCII format and comply to the
  following scheme:

    hd0:images/ferrari=file1
    hd0:images/bubble=file2
    hd0:images/eagle=file3
    hd0:images/bubble=file4
    hd0:images/eagle=file5
    hd0:images/bubble=file6
    hd0:images/bubble=1st_line|2nd_line|3rd_line|...

  First is the name of the file. What follows after the "="
  is the text to be printed below the thumbnail. If more
  than one line is to be printed, it has to be separated
  by "|". Font and fontsize can be specified.

  If you need to create such a list, you may do it
  semi-automatically using a command like the following

    LIST hd0:images/#?.png >ram:namefile.txt LFORMAT="%P%N=%N|(PNG)"

  For details on how to use these options of "C:List", please
  refer to your OS manual. Once you have to create the file,
  you need to make sure, that the "rows" and "colums" are
  properly defined in PagePrint.controlpad (for example,
  if you 34 files (or lines) in namefile.txt you could
  decide for a 6x6 raster - with 2 thumbnails missing to 36).

  Alternatively, you might create a small batch file or
  ARexx script, which automatically adjusts the .controlpad
  file to the constraints resulting from the namefile.txt
  content.


  The following other SV5Operators are used for creation
  of a thumbnail page:

    - AutoBorder
    - AnyTo24Bit
    - ScaleFree
    - DitherFix24
    - AddText


  NOTE:  This SV5Operator discards any input image,
         i.e. it does not in any way require an input
         graphics to operate on (but tools like SView5
         may require you to load one first, in order
         to be able to run this SV5Operator - however
         it does not matter which one you load prior
         to the operation, since it just will be "ignored").

  NOTE2: It is recommended to create your namefile in VMEM:
         - because in turn, if namefile e.g. is "VMEM:dummy"
         then PagePrint will create "VMEM:dummy.out" which
         contains a list of all the filenames (only path+name)
         which were successfully loaded and processed.

  NOTE3: In order to properly handle unknown files it makes
         sense to specify a PLACEHOLDER (cf. below).

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/PagePrint.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - NAMELIST=<filename>
                          ; specifies the image file names,
                          ; which should become part of the thumbail
                          ; overview (one file name per line)
                        - PLACEHOLDER<filename>
                          ; image to be shown for unsupported formats
                        - START=<number>
                          ; specifies the start entry to
                          ; begin from, within the namelist
                        - TEXTNUMLINES=<lines>
                          ; how many lines of text should be
                          ; printed below each thumbnail?

                        - [ plus a few more undocumented options ]

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_PaletteDither "PaletteDither.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  PaletteDither.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  PaletteDither.sv5operator dithers 24 bit RGB graphics 2..256 color
  graphics by using a selectable number of colors from a specified
  fixed palette for that (taken from a given graphics file) and
  calculating the (optional) rest by itself.

  This is useful for creation of ANIMations, where the palette for
  all single frames have to be (mostly) identical or for games and
  other applications where the palette of used graphics have to
  harmonize together.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/PaletteDither.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - COLORDEPTH=<1..8>
                          ; specifies the colordepth of the final,
                          ; dithered graphics (1..8 for 2..256 colors)
                          ; default: 8
                        - DITHERMODE=<BESTPEN|DITHER_FLOYD-STEINBERG>
                          ; whether to just select the best pen or
                          ; do Floyd-Steinberg pixel error adjustment
                          ; default: DITHER_FLOYD-STEINBERG
                        - PALETTEDEPTH=<1..8>
                          ; number of colors (depth) to be taken from the
                          ; fixed palette - the possible rest will be
                          ; generated (if specifying more palette colors
                          ; than available, all available will be taken)
                          ; default: 8
                        - PALETTEFILE=<palette graphics filename>
                          ; any 2..256 color graphics file, of which
                          ; sview5.library is able to extract a
                          ; palette from (for example an IFF-ILBM file,
                          ; but including a BMHD and - maybe empty - BODY).
                          ; Allows to take one graphics as sample for
                          ; the others (concerning the palette).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_Resize "Resize"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Resize.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  Resize.sv5operator resizes any (upto) 256 Color or 24/48 bit graphics
  to new dimensions as supplied by the user (new width and new height).

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Resize.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - NEW_WIDTH=<width>
                          ; new width
                        - NEW_HEIGHT=<height>
                          ; new height

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_Rotate "Rotate"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Rotate.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  Rotate.sv5operator rotates any (upto) 256 Color or 24 bit graphics
  by (default) 90 degrees (reverse clockwise).
  The default behaviour may be overwritten via controlpad settings,
  which also allow 180 and 270 degrees (no extra memory needed: uses
  different algorithm).

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Rotate.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - DEGREES=<90|180|270>
                          ; rotate by how many degrees (reverse clockwise) ?

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_RotateFree "RotateFree"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  RotateFree.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  Rotate.sv5operator rotates any (upto) 256 Color or 24 bit graphics
  by 0..360 (default is 90) degrees (reverse clockwise) about any
  given point (default is the middle, which is width/2, height/2).
  The default behaviour may be overwritten via controlpad settings.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/RotateFree.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - ROTATE_ANGLE=<0..360>
                          ; rotate by how many degrees (reverse clockwise) ?
                        - METHOD=<MIDDLE|GIVENPOINT>
                          ; default is rotation about the middle
                        - X_COORD=<Value>
                          ; if METHOD=GIVENPOINT we need (X/Y)
                          ; Default is (0/0)
                        - Y_COORD=<Value>
                          ; if METHOD=GIVENPOINT we need (X/Y)
                          ; Default is (0/0)
                        - KEEPSIZE
                          ; if this keyword is set, it is NOT tried to
                          ; readjust the image size and to center the
                          ; image, so that parts, which would be out of
                          ; range won't be cut off (which works best
                          ; with (X/Y) pairs in the left, upper quarter)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_Scale50 "Scale50"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Scale50.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  Scale50.sv5operator scales any (upto) 256 Color or 24 bit graphics
  to their half size by default.
  The default behaviour may be overwritten via controlpad settings,
  which also allows to double the size instead.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/Scale50.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - METHOD=<HALF|DOUBLE>
                          ; scale to which size ?

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_ScaleDDA "ScaleDDA"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  ScaleDDA.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  ScaleDDA.sv5operator scales any (upto) 256 Color or 24 bit graphics
  by a given zoom factor, thus increasing its size by a factor larger
  1.0 and decreasing its size by a factor smaller than 1.0

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/ScaleDDA.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - ZOOM_FACTOR=<factor>
                          ; greater than 1.0 (increase size)
                          ; smaller than 1.0 (decrease size)

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_Sharpen "Sharpen.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Sharpen.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  It applies a Sharpen style operator to a given graphics.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_TopToBottom "TopToBottom"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  TopToBottom.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  TopToBottom.sv5operator modifies any supplied source SV_GfxBuffer
  in a way, that it will be swapped from bottom to top
  (works with (upto) 256 Colors and 24 bit files).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SVOPERATOR_XOR "XOR.sv5operator"

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  XOR.sv5operator is an external SV_GfxBuffer modification module
  for sview5.library.

  XOR.sv5operator modifies a graphics in a way, that the color register
  numbers of the supplied picture's pixels are XOR'ed with a given value,
  which may be specified via ControlPads (see below).

  Note, that the supplied XOR value must be be smaller or equal the
  number of colors, thus smaller or equal 2^(depth) - 1.


  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/XOR.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - XORVALUE=<0..255>
                          ; 0 and 255 will not be the best decision ;-)
                          ; Use 15 or something like this.
                          ; Values greater (depth^2)-1 (is: colors-1) won't
                          ; be accepted.

@ENDNODE

# **************************************************************************
# Requirements, Notes And Hints, SV5Prefs, Bibliography, Credits
#

@NODE REQUIREMENTS "Requirements for the SView5-Library Package"

  Generally, you need at least an 68000 Amiga, running with OS 3.1+.
  Better performance results require better software/hardware.

  More requirements (software, hardware, legal):

    o The GUI of the @{"SV5Prefs" LINK LIB_PREFERENCES } program has been designed with StormWizard 2.0,
      so this program needs "wizard.library" V37+ (you can find a copy on Aminet
      under "biz/haage/WizardLibrary.lha").
    ° For usage of the IFF-based SV5Objects, like ILBM, ACBM, PBM, DEEP
      and YUVN, you should take care to have iffparse.library V37+
      on your bootdisk or system partition.
    ° For DataType support with OS 3.x+ you need datatypes.library V39+
      to be present. If it is not present, datatype-support is disabled,
      but you might not need it, anyway.
    ° For being able to use 24 bit Datatypes extension,
      you need Ralph Schmidt's picture.datatype V43 to be installed
      (with ECS/AGA you'll also need a version of cyberncg.library, which
      had been removed from newer pic-dt 43 distributions).
      The picture.datatype V43 which is coming with the Picasso96 RTG
      package will work as well, even with ECS/AGA.
    ° Postscript (TM) support via @{"GhostScript.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_GhostScript } and EPS.sv5object
      requires Ghostscript being correctly installed and configured.
      Without working GhostScript.sv5object and a special flag set,
      EPS.sv5object will not be able to extract any of the Postscript (TM)
      data from EPS(F) files, but only the possibly included preview
      images from the header (which usually are TIFFs).
    ° FIG (-> AmiFIG) support requires both, Ghostscript and @{"AmiFIG.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_AmiFIG },
      being correctly installed and configured.
    ° CGM (-> GPlot) support requires both, Ghostscript and @{"GPlot.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_GPlot },
      being correctly installed and configured.
    ° WMF/AMF/IFF-DR2D/DXF/WPG-Vector (-> MetaView) support requires
      @{"MetaView.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_MetaView }, being correctly installed and configured.
    ° SVG.sv5object, Unpack.sv5object and RGFX.sv5object may/will require xpkmaster.library
      to work fully/properly. The Xpk package can be found on Aminet
      as Aminet:util/pack/xpk_User.lha (also present are xpk_Develop.lha
      and xpk_Source.lha).
    ° AmiIcon.sv5object optionally supports newicon.library for reading/writing
      NewIcons. The NewIcon package can be found on Aminet as Aminet:util/wb/NewIcon#?.lha
      (replace #? with the corresponding version number).
    ° Support for highest PhotoCD resolutions BASE*4 (1536x1024) and BASE*16 (3072x2048)
      does require the NetPBM-Tool "hpcdtoppm" to be installed and configured for
      use with PCD.sv5object. See @{"PCD.sv5object" LINK SVOBJECT_PCD } description for
      more information. The lower resolutions upto BASE (768x512) will work without.

  Additionally there are some more requirements, which do not
  necessarily depend on the OS or the hardware:

    ° Some SV5Objects, SV5Drivers or SV5Operators additionally require
      different hardware/software configurations, but usually this is
      stated within their own documentation.

  Turbo versions will be installed by the installer-script automatically,
  if it makes sense (CPU auto-detection - should even work with 68060).

@ENDNODE

@NODE NOTESANDHINTS "NotesAndHints"

                       Notes and Hints

         @{"How much Memory does this program eat ?!" LINK MEMPROBS    }
          @{"Problems with displaying 24 bit files"   LINK TRUECOLOR_1 }
          @{"Problems with converting 24 bit files"   LINK TRUECOLOR_2 }

@ENDNODE

@NODE MEMPROBS "Memory Usage"

 How much Memory does this program eat ?!
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 Simply enough, there are no fixed limits ...

 sview5.library and its attached SV5Objects, SV5Drivers and
 SV5Operators request as much memory as they need - which directly
 depends on the size of the processed graphics - and there's no
 automatic virtual memory manager or such (I added some virtual
 memory support, but up to now there aren't any modules making
 use of it).

 But actually no CHIP memory is needed for most of the actions
 (only some chunky-to-planar conversion operations and some
 specific SV5Drivers may make use of CHIP memory) - so perhaps
 nearly anything will be performed in FAST ram, when your
 configuration offers enough. You should have at least 2 MB Ram
 at all (1 CHIP, 1 FAST or 2 CHIP), better 4 MB (2 CHIP, 2 FAST)
 or more.

 The large memory usage results out of the buffering-technique, which
 is used with the SView5-Library.

 This technique increases memory usage by using large (full-sized)
 buffers, which often do exist twice e.g. for conversion from
 chunky-pixel to bitplane format or vice versa.

 But this increases SPEED !!

 There are perhaps no "real" multimedia-systems out there, which have
 less than 6 - 16 MB and why shouldn't we use this memory
 (you may BTW use VMM or so, if you don't have so much RAM).

 Anyway, here's a check-list for what you can do to make more memory
 available to sview5.library :

  o first of all, check if there are some background-programs running,
    which you do not really need (especially Commodities).
    Remove them !
  o call "avail flush" in the Shell or select "flushlibs" in the
    WB-debug menu (available when started with "LoadWB -debug").
    (SView5 does also allow flushing libraries directly)
  o decrease the "AddBuffers" values of drives, which you do not
    really need (e.g. DF2, DF3, PC0, ...)
  o last not least : leave/close Workbench, stay in the Shell
  o start your favorite viewer or conversion program (e.g. SView5)
  o again: call "avail flush"
    (this time also all unused SV5Objects and SV5Drivers will be flushed
    out of the memory, so that we later only will have the needed ones
    in Ram)

 If you tried all of the above, and memory still does not suffice,
 you should buy some more SIMMs at your local Computer Shop...

@ENDNODE

@NODE TRUECOLOR_1 "Displaying 24 bit graphics"

  The Problem
  -----------
   "All of my attempts in displaying my really nice 24 bit graphics with
    AGA.sv5object resulted in really ugly colors. What shall I do ?"

  The Reason
  ----------
   You did not set an available or valid 24 bit SV5Operator, which
   could have been used by the selected SV5Driver (e.g. AGA.sv5driver,
   ECS.sv5driver) adjusting the number of colors to less than 256
   (by dithering, conversion to gray, etc.).

  The solution
  ------------
   o Within the SV5Driver's controlpad settings file (e.g. AGA.controlpad,
     ECS.controlpad) you may set "24BITOPERATOR=<operatorname>" and
     specify a specific operator for e.g. dithering 24 bit graphics
     to 256 colors (Dither24Bit), converting them to grayscales
     (ExtractGrayScales) or HAM6/8 (24BitToHam), etc.

   o The same trick may take place for ECS.sv5driver on systems, which
     can't display more than 16/32(64EHB) colors, so that specifying
     the (optional) "8BITOPERATOR=<operatorname>" would allow automatic
     conversion to less colors.

   o Besides this, a special case perhaps perhaps is the combination of
     AGA.sv5driver and JPEG.sv5object, where it may be good for
     performance and memory usage to simply use the internal
     on-the-fly dithering of JPEG.sv5object, which then simply does not
     make 24 bit, but 256 color output anymore, when the colordepth
     controlpad switch has been set as: "COLORDEPTH=8" within
     JPEG.controlpad.

   These default settings intuitively can be changed via @{"SV5Prefs" LINK LIB_PREFERENCES },
   or possibly via your application's GUI as well.

   o An other possibly way is, to always do the dithering only
     when needed - by simply invoking the needed SV5Operator
     fromout your application's GUI.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TRUECOLOR_2 "Converting 24 bit graphics"

  The Problem
  -----------
   You have problems converting from one 24 bit file format into
   other 24 bit file formats ?

  The Reason
  ----------
   Not necessarily all SV5Objects, which support reading of 24 bit files do
   also support writing of 24 bit files.
   SV5Objects, which support writing 24 bit data yet are for example:

    non-lossy
    ---------
    IFF-ILBM     BMP       Targa    SunRaster    PNG
    IFF-DEEP     PCX       PNM      SGI          SVG
    IFF-RGB8     TIFF      QRT      FBM          UtahRLE

    lossy        not for reimport     not importable
    -----        ----------------     --------------
    IFF-YUVN     EPS                  C-Source
    JPEG                              PNM (when in Raw-Mode)
    Limbo
    SPP

  The solution
  ------------
   A temporary solution might be to use other 24 bit programs for
   conversion, if you don't want to use one of the file formats, which
   are already supported.

@ENDNODE

@NODE LIB_PREFERENCES "SV5Prefs"

  © 1994-2004 by Andreas R. Kleinert.
  FREEWARE. All rights reserved. Only to be distributed with SView5-Library.

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  SV5Prefs is the Preferences Program for sview5.library.

  Any specific ControlPad settings for sview5.library,
  sview5support.library and all the SV5Objects, SV5Drivers
  and SV5Operators may be modified fromout here in a comfortable
  GUI-based way - as long as these ControlPad requirements are
  documented in form of a CPInfo-file placed in ENVARC:SView5-Library
  (as usually).

  Additionally, adding and removing of single SV5Objects, SV5Drivers
  or SV5Operators is possible from here, if no other program is accessing
  sview5.library and the related modules at the same time
  (to keep the internal lists valid).


  Inclusion and Exclusion: Explanation
  ------------------------------------
  As one of the newest features of sview5.library, you may also
  decide here, which of the installed SV5Objects, SV5Drivers and/or
  SV5Operators should not be loaded into memory at startup time.
  This works as follows:

   - excluded modules will be written to a specific configuration file
     at ENVARC:SView5-Library and ENV:SView5-Library
     (svobjects.exclude, svdrivers.exclude, svoperators.exclude)
   - excluded modules will not be opened when the library starts
     its initialization phase, which means that these modules will
     never be loaded. May speed up opening and save memory.
     On the other side, these modules are not available as long
     as you don't re-add them to the system, either only temporarily
     or also by re-including.
     So you only should apply this to modules you seldomly or never
     use, but don't want to de-install (everytime) nevertheless.
   - any of these modules may temporarily be loaded via the "Add"
     function of SV5Prefs as well as these (or others) may again
     temporarily be removed
   - SV5Prefs can apply (re)inclusion and exclusion to modules
     currently held in memory
     (to re-include an currently excluded module you at first have to
      re-load it via "Add")

  Inclusion and Exclusion: Overview
  ---------------------------------

     INCLUDE temporarily      ADD
             permanently      ADD, INCLUDE

     EXCLUDE temporarily      REMOVE
             permanently      EXCLUDE, REMOVE

     If you don't need that feature: simply don't use it...


  Commandline Options
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   1. SETANY

      Syntax:      SVPrefs SETANY file NAME [VALUE]
      Explanation: As SET (below) but does not extend the filename,
                   i.e. you can specifiy an absolute path.

   2. SET

      Syntax:      SVPrefs SET file NAME [VALUE]
      Explanation: Can be used to change controlpad settings fromout
                   the Shell or an ARexx script
      Example:  1. SVPrefs SET AGA 24BITOPERATOR Dither24Bit
                   (sets 24BITOPERATOR=Dither24Bit in ENV:SView5-Library/AGA.controlpad)

                2. SVPrefs SET AGA SCREENINFRONT
                   (sets keyword SCREENINFRONT in ENV:SView5-Library/AGA.controlpad)


  Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  GUI has been designed with StormWizard 2.0, so this program needs
  "wizard.library" V37+ (you can find a copy on Aminet under
  "biz/haage/WizardLibrary.lha").

  History
  ~~~~~~~
  SVPrefs' version depends on the version of
  sview5.library it first has been included with.


  V1.1 (31.01.2003) :

   - removed pre-V40 OS support where still present
   - fixed docs

  V1.0 (01.01.2003) :

   - first SView5-Library release version

@ENDNODE

@NODE SUPPORT_LIB "SView5Support-Library"

  © 1994-2004 by Andreas R. Kleinert.
  FREEWARE. All rights reserved. Only to be distributed with SView5-Library.

  Description
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
  sview5support.library contains functions, which are heavily used
  by the sview5.library and its SV5Objects, SV5Drivers and SV5Operators.

  sview5support.library helps saving diskspace by just holding this
  functions for usage by the other libraries, also some sview5.library
  debugging functions are included.

  ControlPad-Switches
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  ControlPad-Name     : "ENV:SView5-Library/superviewsupport.controlpad"
  ControlPad-Commands : - C2P=<OS|SV>
                          ; determines, whether chunky to planar conversion
                          ; is managed via the appropriate OS functions
                          ; or via internal ones.
                          ; Due to various problems with the OS functions
                          ; "SV" is now default.
                          ; Be careful when using "OS" with GfxCards,
                          ; which carelessly patched graphics.library.
                          ;
                          ; NOTE: PPC code will automatically be utilited,
                          ;       when a PPC is available, but only with
                          ;       C2P=SV
                          ;
                          ; Default: SV
                        - MODEGEN=<OS|SV|SVEXT>
                          ; determines, whether viewmode generation should
                          ; rely on internal/OS functions only, or make
                          ; use of P96/CGfx(/PII) functions when available.
                          ; Similar to ModeP. "SV" may cause problems on
                          ; some systems, may work fine on others. "SVEXT"
                          ; was known from the ak-datatypes series as well.
                          ; Note: applicable for OS 3.0 and beyond, only.
                          ; Default: OS

  History
  ~~~~~~~
  V1.4 (31.12.2003) :

   - removed memory pools again (design flaw)

  V1.3 (17.08.2003) :

   - now uses memory pools for ControlPads

  V1.2 (08.03.2003) :

   - internal

  V1.1 (31.01.2003) :

   - removed pre-V40 OS support where still present
   - once again checked for correct SetPatch 43.x depedent code-branching

  V1.0 (01.01.2003) :

   - first SView5-Library release version

@ENDNODE

